N2  - Transcranial direct current stimulation, or tDCS is becoming increasingly popular. However, new techniques like transcranial Random Noise Stimulation (tRNS), transcranial Pulsed Current Stimulation (tPCS), transcranial Alternating Current Stimulation (tACS), and Cranial Electrotherapy Stimulation (CES targeting vagal pathways) are now part of its changing landscape. Beyond tDCS, this practical workshop provides organized exposure to the theory, protocols, circuit-based targeting logic, and clinical integration of various stimulation modalities. Participants will learn about how dysfunction in the prefrontal-limbic-periaqueductal grey (PAG) circuit relates to aggression, emotional regulation problems, inattention, and impulsivity. Customised electrode montages, symptom-to-circuit mapping, and practicality in settings with limited resources will be highlighted. The workshop will also showcase original paediatric tDCS and neuromodulation data collected over 500+ sessions from a rural Indian cohort. These include safety, satisfaction, and symptom response metrics - presented alongside international evidence from RCTs and meta-analyses. Comparative pros and cons of stimulation vs pharmacotherapy and psychosocial interventions will be discussed, challenging common myths and clinician hesitations. Through live demonstrations, case-based problem solving, and guided simulations, attendees will gain both conceptual clarity and procedural confidence in using non-invasive brain stimulation in psychiatric care - especially for children, adolescents, dementia and emotionally dysregulated populations.
