N2  - Background and aims: Alzheimer's disease (AD) is characterized by dysregulated gamma brain oscillations. Transcranial alternating current stimulation (tACS) is a noninvasive brain stimulation technique capable of entraining cerebral oscillations. The aim of this work was to assess the safety and efficacy of home-based gamma tACS applied over the precuneus in patients with mild AD. Methods: This is a double-blind, randomized, sham-controlled clinical trial (ClinicalTrials.gov identifier: NCT05643326) with an open-label extension phase, conducted from October 24, 2022, to October 15, 2024. Fifty patients were randomized to receive either home-based gamma tACS (5 sessions/week, 60 min each) or sham stimulation for 8 weeks (T1, double-blind phase). All participants subsequently received gamma tACS for an additional 8 weeks (T2, open-label phase), followed by an 8-week follow-up (T3). The primary endpoints were safety, feasibility, and clinical efficacy. Secondary endpoints included biological efficacy. Results: Home-based gamma tACS was safe and well-tolerated. We observed a significant enhancement in global cognitive functions, activities of daily living and associative memory performances. Neurophysiological measures showed an increase in cholinergic transmission, coinciding with an increase in gamma power following gamma tACS, effects not seen with sham stimulation. No changes of plasma biomarkers were observed. We did not observe an add-on effect after two repeated treatments with gamma tACS, suggesting that 8 weeks treatment represents the ideal duration instead of 16 weeks treatment. Conclusions: Home-based gamma tACS is feasible, and improves clinical outcomes in AD, with neurophysiological evidence of brain engagement. These findings support further investigation of gamma tACS as a potential therapeutic intervention for AD.
