N2  - Background and aims: Background: Psychogenic Non-Epileptic Seizures (PNES) are a functional neurological disorder often associated with cognitive impairments, particularly in attention. These deficits can negatively impact daily functioning and overall quality of life. Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) is a non-invasive neuromodulation technique that has been explored for cognitive enhancement. This study aims to investigate the effects of tDCS as a cognitive rehabilitation tool for improving attention in PNES patients. Methods: A total of 20 patients diagnosed with PNES were enrolled in a randomized, double-blind, sham-controlled study. Participants received 10 sessions of anodal tDCS targeting the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) over two weeks (2 mA, 20 min per session). Attention was assessed before and after the intervention using standardized neuropsychological tests, including the Digit Span Test, Stroop Test, and Continuous Performance Test (CPT). The sham group received identical electrode placement with minimal stimulation. Results: Patients in the active tDCS group demonstrated significant improvements in attention compared to the sham group. Post-intervention assessments showed increased Digit Span forward scores (p < 0.05), reduced reaction times in the Stroop Test (p < 0.05), and enhanced accuracy in the CPT (p < 0.05). No serious adverse effects were reported. Conclusions: tDCS appears to be a promising intervention for attention deficits in PNES patients. The findings suggest that non-invasive brain stimulation can serve as an effective cognitive rehabilitation tool for functional neurological disorders. Further research with larger sample sizes and extended follow-up periods is needed to confirm the long-term efficacy of tDCS in this population.
