N2  - Background and aims: Cerebral palsy is a neurological disorder, resulting in both motor and cognitive impairments in children. Although, there are no. of rehabilitation strategies designed but therapies targeting neuroplasticity are limited. tDCS is a non invasive technique than promotes neuronal excitablity and plasticity; improving both motor and cognitive functions. This review aims to synthesize evidence on tdcs induced neuroplasticity in CP. Methods: A systematic search was conducted in PubMed, Cochrane, EMBASE, and CINAHL (inception to May 2025) and randomized controlled trials (RCTs), observational studies, and case series involving individuals with CP (age ≤ 21 years) receiving tDCS alone or combined with rehabilitation were selected. Primary outcomes included motor skill acquisition and cognitive metrics. Studies were evaluated based on intervention protocols, cortical targets, outcome measures, and evidence of neuroplastic changes. Results: Evidence suggests that tDCS, particularly when combined with motor training or cognitive tasks, facilitates functional improvements in motor control, gait, and upper limb function in individuals with CP. Anodal stimulation has shown beneficial effects on motor learning and executive functioning. Active tDCS over primary motor cortex significantly enhanced gait parameters compared to sham stimulation. Limited evidence supported tDCS for upper-extremity coordination, with only 2/7 studies showing reduced overflow movements. tDCS paired with physical training boosted motor cortex excitability, evidenced by increased motor-evoked potentials (MEPs) and synaptic potentiation in M1-cerebellar networks. Limited direct evidence existed for cognition, though one study noted improved goal-setting via the Canadian Occupational Performance Measure.tDCS was well-tolerated, with mild adverse effects and low dropout rates. Conclusions: tDCS as neuromodulatory intervention offers a promising bridge between motor and cognitive rehabilitation.
