N2  - Background and aims: Cerebral palsy is characterized by motor impairments; however around 60 % individuals with cerebral palsy also experience cognitive deficits that impact learning, executive function and daily activities. Recent advances have led to the development of various devices such as virtual reality systems, neurofeedback platforms, non-invasive brain stimulation tools, and computerized cognitive training programs aimed for enhancing cognitive abilities. The aim of this review is to identify and examine the efficacy of these biomedical devices in cognitive neuro-rehabilitation. Methods: Systematic literature search was performed across the databases including PubMed, Cochrane library, Scopus and Web of Science from January 2015 to March 2025 following PRISMA guidelines. The RCTs, experimental studies and observational studies were included in this review. The studies were analyzed using risk of bias tools for qualitative assessment. Due to heterogeneity in study designs and outcome measures, a narrative synthesis of findings was undertaken. Results: Interventions varied from virtual-reality training to non-invasive brain stimulation tools like tDCS and TMS. Most studies reported improvements in working memory, attention and executive functions. Although the limitations like- small sample size, lack of long-term followup were reported; yet the high levels of user-friendly engagement was noticed. Conclusions: Biomedical devices show promise as adjunctive tools for cognitive neurorehabilitation in CP, potentially facilitating improvements in cognitive function and overall QoL. However, further large-scale trials with standardized protocols and long-term follow-up are required to confirm these preliminary findings and to determine optimal intervention strategies.
