N2  - Background and aims: Cognitive dysfunction is a common but often overlooked complication in patients with Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE), affecting attention, memory, and executive function. Despite its prevalence, there is no specific pattern of cognitive impairment or established structural abnormalities consistently linked to these deficits in SLE. Non-invasive neuromodulation techniques such as transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) have shown promise in improving cognitive function across various neurological disorders. However, evidence regarding its effectiveness in SLE remains limited. Methods: A total of 36 SLE patients with confirmed cognitive impairment underwent baseline cognitive assessments, including a battery of neuropsychological tests such as the Stroop Test (executive function), Color Trail Test (CTT) (attention), and California Verbal Learning Test (CVLT) (memory). Participants were randomly assigned to either the active tDCS group (N = 18) or the sham stimulation group (N = 18). The intervention included 10 sessions of tDCS targeting the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) combined with cognitive training exercises. Cognitive performance and patient-reported outcomes were reassessed post-intervention. Results: Patients in the active tDCS group demonstrated significant improvements in executive function, attention, and memory compared to the sham group (p < 0.05). Improvements were noted in the Stroop Test (executive function), Color Trail Test (attention), and CVLT (memory). Additionally, self-reported cognitive difficulties and fatigue levels were reduced in the active group. No severe adverse effects were observed, supporting the safety and tolerability of tDCS in SLE patients. Conclusions: These findings suggest that tDCS combined with cognitive rehabilitation may be a viable therapeutic approach for cognitive impairment in SLE.
