N2  - Background and aims: Parkinson's disease (PD) is a growing public health concern in Africa, with cognitive impairment being a significant yet under-addressed challenge. Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) is a low-cost, non-invasive brain stimulation technique that has demonstrated cognitive benefits globally. This study evaluates the efficacy of tDCS in improving cognitive function in PD patients and its potential applicability in resource-limited African healthcare settings. Methods: A systematic review and meta-analysis were conducted using PubMed, Embase, Web of Science and Cochrane Library. Studies published up to January 30, 2025, assessing tDCS effects on cognitive outcomes in PD patients were included. The Cochrane Risk of Bias Tool was used for quality assessment, and a random-effects model was applied for data synthesis. Standardized mean differences (SMD) with 95 % confidence intervals (CI), heterogeneity (I2), and P-values were reported. Results: Twenty-seven studies with 1026 participants were included. tDCS significantly improved overall cognitive function (SMD = 0.78, 95 % CI = 0.61–0.95, I2 = 5 %, P < 0.00001). Notable improvements were observed in executive function (SMD = −0.36, 95 % CI = −0.58 to −0.14, I2 = 3 %, P = 0.002) and language abilities (SMD = 0.54, 95 % CI = 0.26–0.82, I2 = 6 %, P = 0.0002). tDCS also reduced depressive symptoms (SMD = −0.49, 95 % CI = −0.82 to −0.16, I2 = 0 %, P = 0.004). Conclusions: tDCS presents a promising, affordable intervention for PD-related cognitive decline in Africa. Its non-invasive nature and scalability highlight the need for regional clinical trials and healthcare integration.
