N2  - Background and aims: Migraine is a common neurological disorder that often presents with cognitive deficits, including impairments in attention, memory, and executive functions. Non-invasive electrical stimulation techniques—including transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS), transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS), trigeminal nerve stimulation (TNS), and occipital nerve stimulation (ONS)—have emerged as potential interventions for both migraine relief and cognitive modulation.The impact of these modalities on cognition in individuals with migraine has not been systematically synthesized. Methods: This review was conducted in accordance with the PRISMA 2020 guidelines. A systematic search of PubMed, Scopus, Web of Science, and PsycINFO was performed through April 2025. Keywords and MeSH terms included “migraine,” “cognition,” “cognitive function,” “electrical stimulation,” “tDCS,” “TMS,” “trigeminal nerve stimulation,” “occipital nerve stimulation,” and “neuromodulation.” Eligible studies included randomized controlled trials and clinical trials. Results: A total of 532 records were identified, with 22 studies meeting the inclusion criteria. Among these, 10 studies evaluated tDCS or TMS, while 7 examined TNS and 5 focused on ONS. Across modalities, improvements in attention, working memory, and processing speed were observed, especially when stimulation targeted the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex, frontal trigeminal areas, or occipital nerve branches. TNS and ONS showed additional benefits in reducing migraine frequency and severity, which correlated with secondary cognitive improvements. Conclusions: Non-invasive electrical stimulation—including tDCS, TMS, TNS, and ONS—shows potential in improving cognitive functions in individuals with migraine, either through direct neuromodulatory effects or by alleviating migraine-related burden. While early findings are promising, there remains a need for standardized protocols and larger.
