her stimulation intensities (120-135%MSO/RMT: Cohen's d=0.286, small effect size, p = 0.015; 135-150%MSO/RMT: Cohen's d=0.495, medium effect size, p <0.001, Figure 2). Conclusions: TMS-EMG confirms evidence of increased cortical excitability in AD. This was evident at lower intensities with the RMT model (implicating voltage-gated Na+ channels) and higher intensities with the I/OCurve (implicatingAMPAreceptors).TMS may be useful to measure target engagement of novel therapies targeting cortical excitability in AD. (Figure present).
