N2  - Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) has been researched as a potential treatment for various neurological and psychiatric disorders including Alzheimer’s disease (AD). Resting motor threshold (RMT), a neurophysiological measure of motor cortical excitability, is the strength of the applied pulses which can be influenced by neurodegenerative diseases. rTMS pulses are typically given at 90-110% of RMT intensity. In this study, we investigated the relationship between RMT and clinical characteristics. We analyzed data from a large, multi-site clinical trial on repetitive TMS for AD which included data from 147 participants with mild to moderate AD. RMT was assessed bilaterally over the primary motor cortex using single-pulse TMS. Average RMT was computed as the mean of left and right hemisphere measurements and normalized RMT asymmetry was calculated as the absolute difference between left and right hemisphere measurements divided by the average RMT. Data was analyzed using Spearman correlation and Wilcoxon rank sum test. Our results showed a significant negative correlation between age and average RMT (r = -0.164, p = 0.049), and a significant positive correlation between average RMT and the incidence of adverse effects (r = 0.182, p = 0.034). Furthermore, the normalized RMT asymmetry differed significantly between mild and moderate AD participants (p = 0.028), suggesting a potential link between asymmetry of cortical excitability and disease severity. These findings provide insights into how RMT may be affected by age and how RMT asymmetry may reflect increasing severity of AD as was hypothesized. Additionally, the correlation between higher RMT and adverse effects suggests how higher intensities influence the adverse effects as was hypothesized. This work contributes to the understanding of how RMT and its asymmetry may provide valuable information about disease severity and the frequency of adverse effects participants may experience.
