N2  - Abstract _A66_: Presented at the 2024 NYC Neuromodulation Conference Synopsis Parkinson's disease (PD) stems from neurodegeneration of dopaminergic neurons, with lipid accumulation contributing to its progression. Direct Current Stimulation (DCS) alters the lipidome of dopaminergic cells, reducing lipids, including triglycerides and inflammatory species. Multiple stimulations reinforce these effects, promoting oxidative metabolism and survival pathways while decreasing inflammation. Enhanced microvesicle release suggests a potential therapeutic avenue. The study supports a tailored transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) approach, speculating that repeated applications may restore cellular resilience lost in PD progression and interfere with synucleinopathy, paving the way for personalized therapeutic protocols based on blood biomarkers. Background The possibility of modulating electrical activity in the brain is appealing for therapeutic purposes. Transcranial application of direct current to stimulate brain activities, namely tDCS, is a non- invasive neuromodulatory technique leading to synaptic plasticity [1,2]. Its use spans several neurological and psychiatric disorders including major depressive disorder [3], stroke rehabilitation [4,5], chronic pain management [6]. Furthermore, its therapeutic role in motor and cognitive decline in Alzheimer’s and Parkinson’s disease is currently under investigation. tDCS efficacy depends on session number, duration, and current intensity, and the protocols must be tailored to optimise therapeutic outcomes [1]. Thus, the challenge is to elucidate the tDCS mechanism of action, at the systemic, cellular and molecular level that requires the identification of simple models and specific targets that can be used as therapeutic and prognostic markers in the clinic. Several reports assess an altered lipid profile in the brain of PD patients [9] and a role in lipid membrane composition is lately proposed in synucleopathy and in neurodegeneration[8]. We here investigated the effect of DCS on neural cells lipid metabolism, membrane traffic and cellular functions. Methods SHSY5Y neuroblastoma cells were stimulated with DCS (0.5milliA; 0.6 C; electrode size: 0.25 cmˆ2; 20 mins /5x10ˆ5 cells). The effect of single (1) versus multiple (3) stimulations was studied. The lipid profile was evaluated by untargeted LC-MS, the expression of key genes involved in inflammation, oxidative stress defensive response and cellular trophism, lipid oxidation and vesicles formation was evaluated by RT PCR; the production and release of microvesicles (MVs) was evaluated by Nanosight analysis. Results DCS of neural cells induces a deep alteration of the cellular lipidome. Transient changes (24 h) occur after a single stimulation but long lasting (72 h) and more significative changes can be traced after a cycle of repeated stimulation (Fig. 1). In neural cells, multiple DCS modulates structural membrane lipids (PE, PS, PI), downregulates ether-bond bearing lipids and inflammatory lipids (ceramides and lyso-glycerol-phospho lipids). Moreover, it modifies the transcriptional setting, reducing the expression of inflammatory cytokines (TNFα and IL1bβ), increasing the expression of Heme-Oxigenase1 and BDNF, fatty acids oxidation related enzymes and proteins involved in vesicular transport and release (SNARE, sorting nexin and seipin). Finally, DCS treatment enhances extracellular vesicles release, but only multiple stimulation significantly increases the release of exosomes (diameter <120 nM). Discussion The profound changes in lipid profile upon DCS reveals a deep involvement of cell metabolism in response to the treatment. A single stimulation alters cell homeostasis, while multiple stimulation prolongs and stabilizes changes, emphasizing lipid adaptability to the repetitive DCS. The most significant changes are aimed at enhancing oxidative metabolism and energy production, reducing inflammatory lipids, inducing a transcriptional modulation of genes involved in the control of inflammation, counteracting oxidative stress and promoting survival. These changes are associate to an increase in vesicles traffic and release which is impaired in neurodegeneration. Neurodegenerative diseases, such as Parkinson’s and Alzheimer’s, are proteinopathies that can be influenced by changes in the lipid membranes composition, and are thus affected by lipid metabolism. We speculate that tDCS neuromodulation, according to a specific program of repeated application, may promote cellular resilience mechanism that are lost in the progress of PD. Specific markers, possibly detected in the blood, that reflects the metabolism changes in the brain may be able to identify personalized protocol of therapeutic application of tDCS. [Formula presented] References [1] Lefaucheur JP, Antal A, Ayache SS, Benninger DH, Brunelin J, Cogiamanian F, et al. Evidence-based guidelines on the therapeutic use of transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS). Clinical Neurophysiology 2017;128:56–92. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.clinph.2016.10.087. [2] Woods AJ, Antal A, Bikson M, Boggio PS, Brunoni AR, Celnik P, et al. A technical guide to tDCS, and related non-invasive brain stimulation tools. Clin Neurophysiol 2016;127:1031–48. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.clinph.2015.11.012. [3] da Silva R de MF, Brunoni AR, Goerigk S, Batistuzzo MC, Costa DL da C, Diniz JB, et al. Efficacy and safety of transcranial direct current stimulation as an add-on treatment for obsessive-compulsive disorder: a randomized, sham-controlled trial. Neuropsychopharmacology 2021;46:1028–34. https://doi.org/10.1038/s41386-020-00928-w. [4] Orrù G, Conversano C, Hitchcott PK, Gemignani A. Motor stroke recovery after tDCS: a systematic review. Reviews in the Neurosciences 2020;31:201–18. https://doi.org/10.1515/revneuro-2019-0047. [5] Bornheim S, Thibaut A, Beaudart C, Maquet P, Croisier J-L, Kaux J-F. Evaluating the effects of tDCS in stroke patients using functional outcomes: a systematic review. Disability and Rehabilitation 2022;44:13–23. https://doi.org/10.1080/09638288.2020.1759703. [6] Ayache SS, Palm U, Chalah MA, Al-Ani T, Brigno A, Abdellaoui M, et al. Prefrontal tDCS decreases pain in patients with multiple sclerosis. Frontiers in Neuroscience 2016;10:1–12. https://doi.org/10.3389/fnins.2016.00147. [7] Sala G, Bocci T, Borzì V, Parazzini M, Priori A, Ferrarese C. Direct current stimulation enhances neuronal alpha-synuclein degradation in vitro. Scientific Reports 2021;11:1–14. https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-021-81693-8. [8] Jensen MB, Bhatia VK, Jao CC, Rasmussen JE, Pedersen SL, Jensen KJ, et al. Membrane curvature sensing by amphipathic helices: a single liposome study using α-synuclein and annexin B12. J Biol Chem 2011;286:42603–14. https://doi.org/10.1074/jbc.M111.271130. [9] Chiurchiù V, Tiberi M, Matteocci A, Fazio F, Siffeti H, Saracini S, et al. Lipidomics of Bioactive Lipids in Alzheimer’s and Parkinson’s Diseases: Where Are We? International Journal of Molecular Sciences 2022;23. https://doi.org/10.3390/ijms23116235. Disclosures AP is founder and shareholder of Newronika S.P.A. Italy Other authors have nothing to disclose
