N2  - Disclosure Research reported in this publication was supported by the National Institute on Drug Abuse of the National Institutes of Health under Award Number UG3DA054787. The content is solely the responsibility of the authors and does not necessarily represent the official views of the National Institutes of Health. Synopsis: Nicotine use disorder can be conceptualized as a failure in cognitive control and is thought to arise from abnormalities in the reward and control function of the anterior midcingulate cortex (MCC). In this poster, we provide the optimal TMS method for quantifying and modulating the MCC reward (Aim 1) and control function (Aim 2) in nicotine users. In Aim 1, we show that applying TMS over a diffusion- based connectivity target (left prefrontal cortex – MCC) can boost the reward function of the MCC in nicotine users. In Aim 2, we show that applying TMS over an individualized function connectivity-based target (left prefrontal cortex – MCC) can boost the control function of the MCC in nicotine users. The findings from this study may help to develop more precise and effective MCC stimulation protocols according to patients’ structural and functional connectivity profiles and cognitive control deficits. Background: Substance use disorders represents the pathological usurpation of anterior midcingulate cortex (MCC) that normally serves several goal-directed processes (e.g. action selection and control, reward valuation, decision-making)(1, 2). Here, our goal is to optimize a TMS intervention for the purpose of modulating the reward processing and control functions of the MCC, as evaluated by two electrophysiological phenomena called the reward positivity (RewP) and frontal midline theta oscillations (FMT) respectively, in nicotine users. While modulating it is well established that 10-Hz TMS to the left dorsal lateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) (3, 4), the limitations and variability of conventional methods across TMS studies are detrimental for selecting a targeting protocol with high clinical efficacy for MCC modulation. Here, we took a step back and utilized powerful quantitative neuroimaging methods to construct individualized targets based on DLPFC structure, function, and connectivity with the MCC. Our primary goal was to identify the optimal TMS target by systematically measuring the efficacy of various image-based targeting techniques (fMRI, diffusion weighted imaging, resting-state functional connectivity, and cortical thickness) to increase the RewP and FMT in dependent smokers. Methods: In this study, 35 nicotine users (Mean = 4.0 Fagerstrom Test for Nicotine Dependence) were recruited from the surrounding community and engaged in a neuroimaging session, and two TMS/EEG sessions. Participants were randomly assigned to Active (n=17) or Sham (n=18) TMS. All participants received a structural (T1), fMRI, DWI, and resting-state FC scan (Session A) and completed two robot- assisted image-guided (Ri-)TMS sessions. DLPFC targets were identified for each subject within a left DLPFC ‘mask’ and the TMS coil angle was based on simulated TMS e-fields across targets. For the DWI and FC analysis, we identified an MCC "seed" mask based on an established anatomical atlas. At the start of each TMS session, participants were fitted with an EEG cap and asked to navigate a virtual T-maze to find rewards. At the start of Target 1, the robotic arm positioned the TMS coil <1 cm over Target 1 and then 50 rTMS pulses were delivered at 110% of participants’ resting motor threshold (RMT) at 10-Hz continuously over Target 1 before every 10 trials of the T-maze (5 seconds of TMS - 30 seconds of task). A total of 1000 pulses was delivered to Target 1 and 200 T-maze trials completed. Participants then completed the PST to measure post-TMS effects on FMT. Following the completion of the PST, subjects filled out the TCQ and given a 30-40 minute break. Following the break, Target 2 was stimulated using the same protocol as Target 1. On a separate day, Target 3 and Target 4 were stimulated. Thus, each participant will receive TMS to all proposed DLPFC targets across two sessions, and order of targets randomized across subjects. Results: First, we analyzed the effects of TMS on RewP amplitude. Overall, the Active TMS group displayed a larger RewP (M = 2.33 μV) compared to the Sham TMS group (M = .86 μV), p < .0001. Next, when comparing Active vs Sham separately for each Target, DWI targeting displayed the larger effect size (RewP-DWI: Active, M = 2.6, Sham, M = .68; p<.0001, Cohen’s d= 1.5), compared to all other targets (RewP-CT: Active, M = 2.3, Sham, M = .79; p<.05, Cohen’s d= .8 | RewP-RSFC: Active, M= 2.0, Sham, M = .95; p<.05, Cohen’s d= .75 | RewP-fMRI: Active, M = 2.4, Sham, M = 1.1; p<.005, Cohen’s d= .97). Next, we analyzed the effects of TMS on FMT. FMT data was analyzed using a three- factor ANOVA, with feedback valence (positive, negative) and target (fMRI, DWI, RFSC, CT) as within- subjects factor and treatment group (sham, active) as a between-subjects factor. Analysis of the FMT revealed a significant main effect of feedback valence (positive, negative), p = 0.004, with negative feedback eliciting a larger FMT compared to positive feedback. There was a trend for main effect of group (p=0.106). When running separate tests for each Target, this analysis revealed that RSFC targets had the largest effects size on FMT power, such that the active group exhibited a larger FMT following negative feedback (p=.05, Cohen’s d= -.685) and positive feedback (p=.08, Cohen’s d= -.595) compared to sham. For the CT target, active group smokers exhibited a larger FMT following positive feedback (p=.06, Cohen’s d= -.659) compared to sham. A group comparison between Active and Sham for the FMRI, DWI, and CT target only revealed small to medium effects (range Cohen’s d= .243 to -.527). Discussion In this study, we provided compelling evidence that DWI targeting was the optimal protocol to boost the reward function of the MCC in nicotine users, while RSFC was the optimal protocol to boost the control function of the MCC in nicotine users. We hope that our research can help reduce the frequency and severity of neurocognitive deficits among nicotine users and individuals struggling with other substance use disorder, which may ultimately increase substance users’ control over substance use and maintaining treatment goals. References: 1. Buzzell GA, Fedota JR, Roberts DM, McDonald CG (2014): The N2 ERP component as an index of impaired cognitive control in smokers. Neurosci Lett. 563:61-65. 2. Holroyd CB, Umemoto A (2016): The research domain criteria framework: The case for anterior cingulate cortex. Neurosci Biobehav Rev. 71:418-443. 3. Paus T (1999): Imaging the brain before, during, and after transcranial magnetic stimulation. Neuropsychologia. 37:219-224. 4. Cho SS, Strafella AP (2009): rTMS of the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex modulates dopamine release in the ipsilateral anterior cingulate cortex and orbitofrontal cortex. PLoS One. 4:e6725.
