N2  - Abstract : Presented at the 2024 NYC Neuromodulation Conference Synopsis This case study investigates the feasibility and efficacy of a home-based transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) protocol paired with personalized word naming training in a 73-year- old man with logopenic variant primary progressive aphasia (lvPPA). The patient completed 20 sessions of remotely supervised tDCS (RS-tDCS) with concurrent language therapy. Results showed improvements in language outcomes, suggesting the potential of tDCS as an augmentation to speech and language therapy (SLT) in PPA management. Background Primary progressive aphasia (PPA) is a neurocognitive disorder marked by gradual language deterioration [1] across three variants: agrammatic, semantic, and logopenic [2]. SLT is commonly used to manage PPA, but its effectiveness varies [3]. Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) has shown promise in enhancing neural plasticity and improving language function in PPA [4–8]. Practical limitations such as the need for frequent clinic visits and small study sample sizes have hindered its widespread use. This study aims to evaluate the feasibility of a home-based, remotely supervised (RS) tDCS protocol [9,10] paired with SLT to address these limitations and improve language outcomes. Methods A 73-year-old male with lvPPA participated in this study. He underwent 20 daily sessions of RS- tDCS (2.0 mA for 20 minutes) targeting the left inferior frontal gyrus, paired with 45 minutes of personalized word retrieval training following a modified version of the Lexical Retrieval Cascade Treatment [11]. The intervention was conducted at home, 5 days per week for 4 weeks (Monday to Friday), with real-time monitoring via HIPAA-compliant video visits. Language assessments were performed before and after the intervention using the Western Aphasia Battery-Revised (WAB-R) [12] and self-report questionnaires on quality of life and communication abilities. The tDCS equipment, including a 1x1 mini-CT tDCS device, SNAPstrap headset (F7 anode, O1 cathode), and single-use SNAPpad sponge electrodes, was shipped to the patient. Each session began with a clearance and confirmation of headset placement, followed by activation of the tDCS device and initiation of word naming practice. Results The patient completed all 20 sessions as scheduled, reporting only mild and transient adverse events such as brief tingling at the electrode site. Post-intervention assessments showed improvements in language outcomes, including an increase in the WAB-R Aphasia Quotient from 72.0 to 74.9 and in Auditory Verbal Comprehension from 7.3 to 9.0. Spontaneous speech, repetition, and naming and word-finding remained stable. The patient identified more trained items (22/30) compared to untrained items (18/30), indicating a modest benefit from repetitive exposure. Self-reported measures of quality of life and communication abilities, including the SAQOL-39 and PROMIS scales, remained stable, with no significant adverse events reported. Discussion This case study highlights the feasibility and potential benefits of home-based RS-tDCS paired with SLT in managing PPA. The improvements in language function observed in this patient support the potential for tDCS to augment traditional SLT, offering a promising approach for patients with PPA. The protocol's success in a home setting suggests that this approach could be accessible to a broader range of patients, overcoming geographic and logistical barriers. Further investigation through larger randomized controlled trials is warranted to validate these findings, optimize treatment protocols, and establish standardized guidelines for clinical application[13]. References [1] Mesulam M-M. Primary progressive aphasia. Ann Neurol 2001;49:425–32. https://doi.org/10.1002/ana.91. [2] Gorno-Tempini ML, Hillis AE, Weintraub S, Kertesz A, Mendez M, Cappa SF, et al. Classification of primary progressive aphasia and its variants. Neurology 2011;76:1006–14. https://doi.org/10.1212/WNL.0b013e31821103e6. [3] Volkmer A, Rogalski E, Henry M, Taylor-Rubin C, Ruggero L, Khayum R, et al. Speech and language therapy approaches to managing primary progressive aphasia. Pract Neurol 2020;20:154–61. https://doi.org/10.1136/practneurol-2018-001921. [4] Nissim NR, Moberg PJ, Hamilton RH. Efficacy of Noninvasive Brain Stimulation (tDCS or TMS) Paired with Language Therapy in the Treatment of Primary Progressive Aphasia: An Exploratory Meta-Analysis. Brain Sci 2020;10:597. https://doi.org/10.3390/brainsci10090597. [5] Tsapkini K, Webster KT, Ficek BN, Desmond JE, Onyike CU, Rapp B, et al. Electrical brain stimulation in different variants of primary progressive aphasia: A randomized clinical trial. Alzheimers Dement Transl Res Clin Interv 2018;4:461–72. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.trci.2018.08.002. [6] Coemans S, Struys E, Vandenborre D, Wilssens I, Engelborghs S, Paquier P, et al. A Systematic Review of Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation in Primary Progressive Aphasia: Methodological Considerations. Front Aging Neurosci 2021;13:710818. https://doi.org/10.3389/fnagi.2021.710818. [7] McConathey EM, White NC, Gervits F, Ash S, Coslett HB, Grossman M, et al. Baseline Performance Predicts tDCS-Mediated Improvements in Language Symptoms in Primary Progressive Aphasia. Front Hum Neurosci 2017;11. https://doi.org/10.3389/fnhum.2017.00347. [8] Zhao Y, Ficek B, Webster K, Frangakis C, Caffo B, Hillis AE, et al. White Matter Integrity Predicts Electrical Stimulation (tDCS) and Language Therapy Effects in Primary Progressive Aphasia. Neurorehabil Neural Repair 2021;35:44–57. https://doi.org/10.1177/1545968320971741. [9] Charvet LE, Shaw MT, Bikson M, Woods AJ, Knotkova H. Supervised transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) at home: A guide for clinical research and practice. Brain Stimulat 2020;13:686–93. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.brs.2020.02.011. [10] Pilloni G, Vogel-Eyny A, Lustberg M, Best P, Malik M, Walton-Masters L, et al. Tolerability and feasibility of at-home remotely supervised transcranial direct current stimulation (RS- tDCS): Single-center evidence from 6,779 sessions. Brain Stimulat 2022;15:707–16. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.brs.2022.04.014. [11] Henry ML, Hubbard HI, Grasso SM, Dial HR, Beeson PM, Miller BL, et al. Treatment for Word Retrieval in Semantic and Logopenic Variants of Primary Progressive Aphasia: Immediate and Long-Term Outcomes. J Speech Lang Hear Res JSLHR 2019;62:2723–49. https://doi.org/10.1044/2018_JSLHR-L-18-0144. [12] Western Aphasia Battery-Revised n.d. https://psycnet.apa.org/doiLanding?doi=10.1037%2Ft15168-000 (accessed July 10, 2024). [13] Roheger M, Riemann S, Brauer A, McGowan E, Grittner U, Flöel A, et al. Non- pharmacological interventions for improving language and communication in people with primary progressive aphasia. Cochrane Database Syst Rev 2024;5:CD015067. https://doi.org/10.1002/14651858.CD015067.pub2. Disclosures Nothing to be disclosed by any author(s).
