N2  - Abstract B 96: Presented at the 2024 NYC Neuromodulation Conference Synopsis Language dysfunction is receiving increasing attention as a prevalent and early affected cognitive domain in individuals with multiple sclerosis (MS). This pilot tested the potential effect of transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) on language function in 32 MS participants, targeting left/right dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (dlPFC) and left/right inferior frontal gyrus (IFG) versus sham. Verbal fluency was evaluated pre and post intervention. Anodal stimulation of left dlPFC improved semantic fluency, while other regions showed no significant effects. The left dlPFC group showed higher semantic scores compared to other anodal groups, suggesting targeted dlPFC stimulation may be a promising approach for improving language function in MS patients. Background Language dysfunction has only recently begun to receive widespread attention as an important affected domain in multiple sclerosis (MS)[1, 2]. Word finding difficulties have been identified as a primary cognitive issue reported by MS patients early in their disease trajectory[3]. Challenges in language production, such as verbal fluency[4], word/sentence repetition, and accessing lexical or syntactic information, are prevalent[1, 3]. The underlying neural mechanisms involve a distributed network across the frontoparietal cortices, notably within the inferior frontal cortex and the posterior superior temporal cortex, as well as temporal regions of the default-mode network (DMN) essential for language tasks[5]. Research highlights the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (dlPFC)'s pivotal role in language comprehension and production, necessitating cognitive control and working memory[6]. Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) has emerged as a potential therapeutic approach, enhancing language processing in healthy individuals and various clinical populations[7]. Previous studies demonstrate that anodal tDCS can significantly improve verbal fluency[8], word retrieval[9], picture naming[10], verbal learning, and artificial grammar learning[11], focusing on the left/right IFG and dlPFC[12]. To date, no work to our knowledge has studied effects of tDCS on language function in MS. The aim of this study is to assess the effects of tDCS on enhancing language function in individuals with MS. Methods Patients aged <45, diagnosed with the relapsing-remitting MS (RRMS) based on the modified McDonald’s 2010 criteria, with mild Expanded Disability Status Scale score (EDSS) < 3, fatigue severity scale (FSS) < 6, Hospital Anxiety and Depression Scale (HADS) < 12, and scoring less than 1 SD below published norms for language tests, were included. Potential participants with a documented history of mood or sleep disorders, current use of psychiatric medications, previous brain surgery or the presence of brain clips, a history of seizures, or left-handedness were excluded. Each patient was assigned to one of eight groups: 1. Left IFG tDCS, 2. Left IFG sham, 3. Right IFG tDCS, 4. Right IFG sham, 5. Left DLPFC tDCS, 6. Left DLPFC sham, 7. Right DLPFC tDCS, 8. Right DLPFC sham. Patients completed the Brief International Cognitive Assessment for MS (BICAMS) at baseline, and language performance was evaluated with tests of phonemic and semantic fluency at baseline and immediately after intervention. The BICAMS includes three subtests: The oral version of the Symbol Digit Modalities Test (SDMT), the initial learning trials from California Verbal Learning Test,2nd edition (CVLT-II) and Brief Visuospatial Memory Test Revised (BVMT-R). All patients were randomized to receive one 30-minute session 2 mA of either tDCS or sham intervention. Statistical anlaysis for each group was performed using paired Students’s test (before vs after) and analysis of covariance (ANCOVA) to compare the language function and regions stimulation between groups. Results A total of 32 patients with MS participated in the study (84% women and 16 % men, age: 36.4 ±7.3 years). Average disease duration was 66 months. The mean EDSS was 1.45±0.56, FSS 3.02±1.07, and HADS score 12.34 ± 4.68. Regarding baseline cognitive status, the mean score on SDMT was 40.31±11.84. The mean score on CVLT was 42±11.97. Mean score on BVMT-R was 15.03±8.88. Mean FAS score was 27.28 ± 8.17 and mean Animals score was 8.34 ± 5.07. In the left anodal dlPFC region, there was a significant effect of stimulation on the phonemic (26.83 ± 8.47 vs. 33.66 ±7.55, p =0.04) and semantic task (18.5 ± 5.12 vs. 23.83 ± 3.86) before and after intervention. However, there was no statistically significant effect of stimulation on SDMT (38.66 ± 8.45 vs. 43.16 ± 7.65, p = 0.08). The group by time interaction analysis revealed that participants achieved higher scores in semantic fluency than sham group (23.83 ± 3.86 vs. 17.66 ± 2.08 p = 0.03). During anodal right dlPFC stimulation, there was significant effect of stimulation on the phonemic (22.4 ±6.9 vs. 28.2 ± 8.31, p = 0.04) but decreased semantic fluency (18 ± 6.08 vs 12.8 ± 4.43 p = 0.03) pre and post intervention. However, no significant group by time interaction was observed. In the left anodal IFG, there was an improvement between before and after stimulation on SDMT (32 ± 15.34 vs. 36 ± 16.39, p = 0.02) and phonemic fluency (26.25 ± 7.41 vs. 32.5 ± 12.12, p = 0.04). However, in the semantic task the performance was worse (19.25 ±7.04 vs. 11.5 ± 5.32, p = 0.03). There was no significant group by time interaction. In terms of right anodal IFG, no significant effect of stimulation observed on phonemic, semantic, and SDMT. The significant group by time interaction indicated that the left dlPFC group showed a higher semantic score compared to other anodal stimulation conditions (p = 0.001). The results revealed that the left dlPFC exhibited domain-specific effects on language function. Upregulation of the left dlPFC resulted in improved semantic fluency, whereas upregulation of the right dlPFC, left IFG, and right IFG did not lead to enhanced language function (Figure 1). [Formula presented] Discussion A meta-analysis evaluating the reliability of tDCS effects on language in non-MS clinical populations suggests targeting the left prefrontal cortex can enhance verbal fluency[13]. This is supported by evidence from various neurological conditions, including stroke, Parkinson's disease, and Alzheimer's, where tDCS has shown promise in improving language function[14- 16]. The Memory-Unification-Control model posits a language processing control mechanism within the dlPFC, corroborated by fMRI studies showing left dlPFC activation during language tasks[17, 18]. Interestingly, cathodal tDCS over the left dlPFC affects language comprehension and production differently, suggesting nuanced effects of stimulation[19]. Anodal stimulation on the left dlPFC has shown significant effects on language tasks, indicating its potential for managing language deficits in MS, despite inconsistencies in behavioral outcomes[20]. The improvement in semantic fluency with left dlPFC stimulation is promising for tDCS in treating MS-related language deficits. However, the lack of effects in other areas points to the complexity of language networks and the need for refined research on stimulation parameters. Future research is needed to better understand the underlying mechanisms of these effects, using neuroimaging and electrophysiology to uncover the neural changes tDCS induces. Investigating the persistence of these effects and optimizing stimulation protocols, and assessing the combination of tDCS with other rehabilitation methods could greatly enhance its therapeutic potential for language dysfunction in MS. References 1. Šubert, M., et al., Lexical and syntactic deficits analyzed via automated natural language processing: the new monitoring tool in multiple sclerosis. Therapeutic Advances in Neurological Disorders, 2023. 16: p. 17562864231180719. 2. Rook, J., et al., Language impairments in people with autoimmune neurological diseases: A scoping review. Journal of Communication Disorders, 2023: p. 106368. 3. Brandstadter, R., et al., Word-finding difficulty is a prevalent disease-related deficit in early multiple sclerosis. Multiple Sclerosis Journal, 2020. 26(13): p. 1752-1764. 4. Devere, T.R., J.L. Trotter, and A.H. Cross, Acute aphasia in multiple sclerosis. Archives of neurology, 2000. 57(8): p. 1207-1209. 5. Tomasi, D. and N.D. Volkow, Resting functional connectivity of language networks: characterization and reproducibility. Molecular psychiatry, 2012. 17(8): p. 841-854. 6. Klaus, J. and D.J. Schutter, The role of left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex in language processing. Neuroscience, 2018. 377: p. 197-205. 7. Monti, A., et al., Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) and language. Journal of Neurology, Neurosurgery & Psychiatry, 2013. 84(8): p. 832-842. 8. Cattaneo, Z., A. Pisoni, and C. Papagno, Transcranial direct current stimulation over Broca's region improves phonemic and semantic fluency in healthy individuals. Neuroscience, 2011. 183: p. 64-70. 9. Fiori, V., et al., Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation Improves Word Retrieval in Healthy and Nonfluent Aphasic Subjects. Journal of Cognitive Neuroscience, 2011. 23(9): p. 2309- 2323. 10. Holland, R., et al., Speech facilitation by left inferior frontal cortex stimulation. Current Biology, 2011. 21(16): p. 1403-1407. 11. De Vries, M.H., et al., Electrical stimulation of Broca's area enhances implicit learning of an artificial grammar. Journal of cognitive neuroscience, 2010. 22(11): p. 2427-2436. 12. Nejati, V., R. Estaji, and Z. Helisaz, Transcranial Direct-Current Stimulation Improves Verbal Fluency in Children with Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD). Brain Sciences, 2023. 13(9): p. 1257. 13. Price, A.R., et al., A meta-analysis of transcranial direct current stimulation studies examining the reliability of effects on language measures. Brain stimulation, 2015. 8(6): p. 1093-1100. 14. Fridriksson, J., et al., Transcranial direct current stimulation vs sham stimulation to treat aphasia after stroke: a randomized clinical trial. JAMA neurology, 2018. 75(12): p. 1470- 1476. 15. Cammisuli, D.M., et al., Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) as a useful rehabilitation strategy to improve cognition in patients with Alzheimer's Disease and Parkinson's Disease: an updated systematic review of randomized controlled trials. Frontiers in Neurology, 2022. 12: p. 798191. 16. Pereira, J.B., et al., Modulation of verbal fluency networks by transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) in Parkinson’s disease. Brain stimulation, 2013. 6(1): p. 16-24. 17. Hsu, N.S., S.M. Jaeggi, and J.M. Novick, A common neural hub resolves syntactic and non-syntactic conflict through cooperation with task-specific networks. Brain and language, 2017. 166: p. 63-77. 18. Humphreys, G.F. and S.P. Gennari, Competitive mechanisms in sentence processing: Common and distinct production and reading comprehension networks linked to the prefrontal cortex. NeuroImage, 2014. 84: p. 354-366. 19. Klaus, J. and D.J.L.G. Schutter, The Role of Left Dorsolateral Prefrontal Cortex in Language Processing. Neuroscience, 2018. 377: p. 197-205. 20. Radman, N., et al., Dorsolateral prefrontal transcranial direct current stimulation modulates language processing but does not facilitate overt second language word production. Frontiers in Neuroscience, 2018. 12: p. 490. Disclosure Nothing to disclose by any authors.
