N2  - Abstract A3: Presented at the 2024 NYC Neuromodulation Conference Synopsis: Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) may augment cognitive control, but it is unclear how brain stimulation interacts with endogenous activity within stimulated circuits. We examined state-dependent effects of rTMS by applying stimulation during tasks that evoke cognitive control versus perceptual states. rTMS augmented clinically relevant metrics of cognitive control and perturbed theta band oscillations more strongly if participants were completing a cognitive control task at the time of stimulation. These findings suggest that rTMS may produce more favorable effects if it is delivered during endogenous activation of the stimulated circuits, providing implications that may guide protocol development to enhance the efficacy of psychiatric neuromodulation. Background: The effects of neuromodulation may depend not only on the properties of the stimulation, but also the susceptibility of the stimulated brain region to being activated(Bradley et al., 2022; Sack et al., 2023; Silvanto et al., 2008). However, little consideration has been given to how fluctuations in these brain states influence the effects of brain stimulation. This may contribute to the wide variation in efficacy of neuromodulation for psychiatric disorders(McClintock et al., 2018). Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) is typically applied therapeutically to the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC)(Li et al., 2017), which forms part of the functional circuitry of cognitive control. This is the ability to direct cognitive resources to goal-relevant information while suppressing non-relevant information(Gabrys et al., 2018). rTMS may reduce psychiatric symptoms by augmenting that control and improving patients’ redirection of maladaptive cognitive patterns(Arnsten et al., 2012; Li et al., 2017; Solomon et al., 2009; Torrent et al., 2012; Widge et al., 2019). Thus far, the interaction of prefrontal rTMS with internal states of cognitive control has been unexplored. Here, we examined how prefrontal rTMS affects cognitive control, depending on the state of those circuits during stimulation. We hypothesized that rTMS would augment performance in a cognitive control task more strongly if it is applied while those relevant circuits are endogenously activated. In addition, given the role of prefrontal theta band oscillations in executive function(Basharpoor et al., 2021; Cavanagh & Frank, 2014; Cavanagh & Shackman, 2015; Jacobs et al., 2006; Karakaş, 2020; Mizuhara & Yamaguchi, 2007; Soltani Zangbar et al., 2020), we hypothesized that prefrontal rTMS would perturb prefrontal theta activity more strongly when it is applied during endogenous engagement of cognitive control circuits. Methods: Participants (N = 17) received intermittent bursts of prefrontal rTMS whilst completing a behavioral task that requires cognitive control, the translational orientation pattern expectancy (TOPX) task. TOPX presents a sequence of two Gabor patches, a cue and a probe, which can either be valid or invalid. Participants must indicate whether or not the target sequence (valid cue AND valid probe) was presented in that trial. The target sequence is presented more often than not, which produces a response bias that must be countermanded when an invalid probe is presented (cognitive control). In a separate session (control condition; 1 week apart, counterbalanced), participants received rTMS while completing a perceptual task that does not require cognitive control and is thus less DLPFC dependent. We also quantified cognitive control via TOPX before and after receiving rTMS. We applied hierarchical drift diffusion modelling of reaction time and accuracy of responses in TOPX to assess the contribution of decision-making parameters toward proactive versus reactive cognitive control. In addition, we recorded electroencephalography (EEG) throughout sessions to evaluate event-related spectral perturbations (ERSPs) to TMS during the cognitive control versus perceptual tasks. EEG data were time-frequency decomposed with modified Morlet wavelets at frequencies 3-50 Hz and with a pre-stimulus baseline correction from -500 to -100 ms relative to stimulation. We compared theta-band (4-8 Hz) prefrontal ERSPs to single and repetitive TMS during the cognitive control versus perceptual tasks. Results: We demonstrate a state-dependent enhancement of cognitive control by rTMS. Specifically, modulation of response accuracy (representing cognitive control capacity) by rTMS depended on the behavioral state at the time of stimulation. A linear mixed-effects model of response accuracy indicated a significant interaction of block (pre-rTMS, post-rTMS) with rTMS task type (cognitive control, perceptual), F(1,34.03) = 6.68, p = .014. Response accuracy in the cognitive control task increased from baseline after rTMS was applied during the cognitive control task (t(36) = 2.51, p = .017), but not when rTMS was applied during the perceptual task (t(36) = -1.12, p= .269). Proactive behavioral control (the ability to use contextual information to guide responses) showed a similar state-dependent modulation by rTMS, F(1,36.79) = 6.07, p = .022, showing an increase from baseline after rTMS was applied during the cognitive control task (t(40)= 2.41, p = .021), but not after it was applied during the perceptual task (t(40) = -0.21, p = .836). We also examined the modulation of drift diffusion parameters by rTMS. The best fitting model allowed the rate of evidence accumulation and boundary separation to vary by trial type (cue and probe), permitted the bias to vary by cue, and held non-decision time constant within subjects(Shen et al., 2024). Change in the degree of bias toward cue-driven proactive control versus probe-driven reactive control after rTMS depended on the behavioral state at the time of stimulation, F(3,88) = 47.96, p < .001 (see Figure 1A). In contrast, drift rate (p = .197) and boundary separation (p = .121) did not change after rTMS as a function of the behavioral state at the time of stimulation. When rTMS was administered during the cognitive control task, response bias increased from baseline toward cue-derived proactive responding (t(20) = 9.52, p <.001), and the degree of bias shifted away from probe-derived habitual responding (t(20) = -5.77, p < .001). In contrast, after rTMS was administered during the perceptual task, bias toward habitual responses increased from baseline (t(20) = 7.04, p < .001) and there was no change in the degree of bias toward proactive responding (t(20) = 1.39, p = .182). Examination of prefrontal ERSPs to TMS during the cognitive control versus perceptual tasks suggested differential oscillatory responses to stimulation that may underly the behavioral enhancement we observed after rTMS was applied during cognitive control. We averaged ERSPs across frequencies within the theta band and across the 700 ms following TMS, and compared the amplitude of the ERSPs between the cognitive control and perceptual tasks. We evaluated the difference in ERSP amplitude between tasks against a null distribution by shuffling condition labels randomly across 1000 permutations. Following single-pulse TMS, prefrontal theta band ERSPs were, on average, 1.16 dB larger (SD = 0.22) during the cognitive control task in comparison to the perceptual task (p < .001; Figure 1B). Similarly, following the rTMS train, prefrontal ERSPs in the theta band were 0.55 dB larger (SD = 0.24) during the cognitive control task, relative to the perceptual one (p < .001; Figure 1C). Discussion: These findings demonstrate how prefrontal rTMS may interact with endogenous activity within circuits subject to stimulation. After rTMS was administered during a behavioral state that actively engaged relevant cognitive control circuits, we observed an improvement of clinically relevant metrics of cognitive control that outlasted the time of stimulation. That is, rTMS facilitated subjects’ capacity for cognitive control, improved proactive responding, and reduced habitual responding. On the other hand, when rTMS was applied during a behavioral state that did not engage cognitive control circuits to the same degree, there was no benefit afforded to their performance in the cognitive control task and subjects demonstrated a bias of evidence accumulation toward habitual responding. Furthermore, prefrontal oscillatory responses following both single-pulse TMS and rTMS trains were enhanced in the theta band when they were applied during engagement of cognitive control. Given the role of theta band activity in executive functioning, the modulation of that activity by TMS may provide a mechanistic means by which rTMS could facilitate cognitive control in a state-dependent manner. These findings provide important implications for guiding the development of protocols to enhance the efficacy of psychiatric neuromodulation. In particular, our protocol used to engage circuits that are subject to rTMS may be exploited to produce more robust and reliable effects of stimulation, which has potential to enhance and/or accelerate the antidepressant response to rTMS. [Formula presented] References: Arnsten, A. F. T., Wang, M. J., & Paspalas, C. D. (2012). Neuromodulation of thought: Flexibilities and vulnerabilities in prefrontal cortical network synapses. Neuron, 76(1), 223–239. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neuron.2012.08.038 Basharpoor, S., Heidari, F., & Molavi, P. (2021). EEG coherence in theta, alpha, and beta bands in frontal regions and executive functions. Applied Neuropsychology: Adult, 28(3), 310–317. https://doi.org/10.1080/23279095.2019.1632860 Bradley, C., Nydam, A. S., Dux, P. E., & Mattingley, J. B. (2022). State-dependent effects of neural stimulation on brain function and cognition. Nature Reviews Neuroscience 2022 23:8, 23(8), 459–475. https://doi.org/10.1038/s41583-022-00598-1 Cavanagh, J. F., & Frank, M. J. (2014). Frontal theta as a mechanism for cognitive control. Trends in Cognitive Sciences, 18(8), 414–421. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tics.2014.04.012 Cavanagh, J. F., & Shackman, A. J. (2015). Frontal midline theta reflects anxiety and cognitive control: Meta-analytic evidence. Journal of Physiology-Paris, 109(1), 3–15. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jphysparis.2014.04.003 Gabrys, R. L., Tabri, N., Anisman, H., & Matheson, K. (2018). Cognitive control and flexibility in the context of stress and depressive symptoms: The cognitive control and flexibility questionnaire. Frontiers in Psychology, 9(NOV), 2219. https://doi.org/10.3389/FPSYG.2018.02219/BIBTEX Jacobs, J., Hwang, G., Curran, T., & Kahana, M. J. (2006). EEG oscillations and recognition memory: Theta correlates of memory retrieval and decision making. NeuroImage, 32(2), 978–987. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neuroimage.2006.02.018 Karakaş, S. (2020). A review of theta oscillation and its functional correlates. International Journal of Psychophysiology, 157, 82–99. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijpsycho.2020.04.008 Li, Y., Wang, L., Jia, M., Guo, J., Wang, H., & Wang, M. (2017). The effects of high-frequency rTMS over the left DLPFC on cognitive control in young healthy participants. PLoS ONE, 12(6), e0179430. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0179430 McClintock, S. M., Reti, I. M., Carpenter, L. L., McDonald, W. M., Dubin, M., Taylor, S. F., Cook, I. A., O’Reardon, J., Husain, M. M., Wall, C., Krystal, A. D., Sampson, S. M., Morales, O., Nelson, B. G., Latoussakis, V., George, M. S., & Lisanby, S. H. (2018). Consensus recommendations for the clinical application of repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) in the treatment of depression. Journal of Clinical Psychiatry, 79(1), 35–48. https://doi.org/10.4088/JCP.16cs10905 Mizuhara, H., & Yamaguchi, Y. (2007). Human cortical circuits for central executive function emerge by theta phase synchronization. NeuroImage, 36(1), 232–244. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neuroimage.2007.02.026 Sack, A. T., Paneva, J., Küthe, T., Dijkstra, E., Zwienenberg, L., Arns, M., & Schuhmann, T. (2023). Target engagement and brain state dependence of transcranial magnetic stimulation: Implications for clinical practice. Biological Psychiatry. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.biopsych.2023.09.011 Shen, C., Calvin, O. L., Rawls, E., Redish, A. D., & Sponheim, S. R. (2024). Clarifying Cognitive Control Deficits in Psychosis via Drift Diffusion Modeling and Attractor Dynamics. Schizophrenia Bulletin, sbae014. https://doi.org/10.1093/schbul/sbae014 Silvanto, J., Muggleton, N., & Walsh, V. (2008). State-dependency in brain stimulation studies of perception and cognition. Trends in Cognitive Sciences, 12(12), 447–454. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.tics.2008.09.004 Solomon, M., Ozonoff, S. J., Ursu, S., Ravizza, S., Cummings, N., Ly, S., & Carter, C. S. (2009). The neural substrates of cognitive control deficits in autism spectrum disorders. Neuropsychologia, 47(12), 2515–2526. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.neuropsychologia.2009.04.019 Soltani Zangbar, H., Ghadiri, T., Seyedi Vafaee, M., Ebrahimi Kalan, A., Fallahi, S., Ghorbani, M., & Shahabi, P. (2020). Theta Oscillations Through Hippocampal/Prefrontal Pathway: Importance in Cognitive Performances. Brain Connectivity, 10(4), 157–169. https://doi.org/10.1089/brain.2019.0733 Torrent, C., Martinez-Arán, A., Del Mar Bonnin, C., Reinares, M., Daban, C., Solé, B., Rosa, A. R., Tabarés-Seisdedos, R., Popovic, D., Salamero, M., & Vieta, E. (2012). Long-term outcome of cognitive impairment in bipolar disorder. Journal of Clinical Psychiatry, 73(7). https://doi.org/10.4088/JCP.11m07471 Widge, A. S., Bilge, M. T., Montana, R., Chang, W., Rodriguez, C. I., Deckersbach, T., Carpenter, L. L., Kalin, N. H., & Nemeroff, C. B. (2019). Electroencephalographic Biomarkers for Treatment Response Prediction in Major Depressive Illness: A Meta- Analysis. The American Journal of Psychiatry, 176(1), 44–56. https://doi.org/10.1176/appi.ajp