N2  - Pridopidine is a potent sigma-1 receptor agonist in development for HD. The phase 3 PROOF-HD trial evaluated the safety and efficacy of pridopidine (45mg bid) in manifest HD participants (total functional capacity, TFC>7). PROOF-HD included a 78-week double-blind period followed by a 26-week Open Label Extension (OLE). In prespecified analyses of participants off antidopaminergic medications (ADMs: VMAT2 inhibitors and antipsychotics), pridopidine showed clinically meaningful, unprecedented improvements from baseline to wk52 in key outcomes and reduced decline throughout the 78-week period as compared with placebo in progression (cUHDRS [wk52 Δ0.43, p=0.04; wk78 Δ0.50, p=0.08]), cognition (Stoop Word Reading, SWR [wk52 Δ4.22, p=0.02; wk78 Δ2.82, p=0.20]), and motor function (Q-Motor Finger Tapping (FT) Inter-onset Interval (IOI) (wk52 Δ-22.84, p=0.04; wk78 Δ-34.23, p=0.005)). Pridopidine also preserved quality-of-life through wk78. In participants off ADMs, the benefits of pridopidine were maintained through the OLE wk104 timepoint in progression (cUHDRS (Δ1.48, p=0.009)), function (TFC (Δ1.01, p=0.05)), cognition (SWR (Δ7.9, p=0.04)), and motor function (Q-Motor FT IOI (Δ-110.0ms, p=0.0001) and total motor score (TMS (Δ-4.4, p=0.040)) as compared with propensity matched controls from the TRACK-HD observational study. Pridopidine was well tolerated with a safety profile comparable to placebo. Pridopidine is a CYP2D6 inhibitor, potentially influencing CYP2D6-dependent metabolism of certain ADMs. However, participants administered low doses of ADMs (per regulatory indication) continued to experience pridopidine benefits. Pridopidine demonstrates clinically meaningful benefits across multiple domains including function, clinical progression, cognition, and motor function, with consistent and sustained effects observed in subjects off or on low doses of ADMs.
