N2  - Background: Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) is a promising neuromodulation approach for addressing cognitive deficits in neuropsychiatric disorders. However, results show significant heterogeneity, partially due to patient-specific differences in pathophysiology and/or normal neurobiology, highlighting the need for precision approaches to optimizing efficacy. Methods: To develop biotypes of tDCS responsiveness, we employed unsupervised machine learning (ML) to stratify tDCS outcomes based on resting-state EEG data in individuals with ADHD, Substance Use Disorders, and healthy controls (n=102). Participants underwent tDCS with pre-/post-stimulation executive function task assessments (Flanker, N-Back, Stop Signal) and EEG. Responder and Non-Responder labels were determined based on task performance changes from pre- to post-tDCS. Baseline EEG profiles were established by extracting spectral features including relative and absolute power, entropy, and spectral exponent (1/f slope of power spectral density). Feature selection used ML-based preprocessing tool DREAMER (Data Readiness for ML Research) and Random Forest importances. Similarity Network Fusion (SNF), an unsupervised algorithm, identified EEG-based clusters. We assessed correlations between clusters and post-tDCS outcomes and evaluated EEG feature contributions via normalized mutual information and ANOVA. Results: Behavioral and electrophysiological analyses showed significant performance (p=0.0002, p=0.01817) and EEG (p < 2.2e-16) differences across the clusters. The responder cluster showed higher alpha power and a steeper 1/f slope, indicating optimal inhibitory control. SNF-derived clusters outperformed diagnostic categories in predicting tDCS response (p=0.018), highlighting the value of data-driven stratification. Conclusions: Our approach identified distinct neurophysiological signatures corresponding to tDCS outcomes. Leveraging unsupervised ML and resting-state EEG, our study advances precise tDCS outcome prediction, informing personalized neuropsychiatric interventions and treatment selection. Keywords: Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation/tDCS, Machine Learning, EEG, Neuromodulation
