N2  - Background: Schizophrenia spectrum disorders (SSDs) often feature debilitating social cognitive deficits, which lack treatment options. This target engagement study implemented our group’s personalized repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) targeting pipeline to examine the effect of individually-targeted rTMS on social cognitive network functional connectivity in individuals with SSDs. Methods: A multi-center two-week, double-blind, randomized clinical trial was conducted comparing 10Hz rTMS and intermittent theta burst stimulation (iTBS) to sham stimulation of the dorsomedial prefrontal cortex in adults with SSDs. Participants completed magnetic resonance imaging, including the Empathic Accuracy task, pre- and post-treatment. Neurostimulation was optimized using our group’s Bayesian Optimization Of NeuroStimulation (BOONStim) pipeline, including individualized electric field modeling and functional connectivity mapping. Within-mentalizing and between mentalizing-mirroring network functional connectivity metrics were calculated pre- and post-rTMS. Effect sizes were used to compare the magnitude of changes after 10Hz rTMS and iTBS versus sham. Results: Imaging analyses included 43 participants (10Hz rTMS N=15, iTBS N=15, sham N=13). There was a greater increase in mentalizing network connectivity following iTBS (d=0.53, 95% CI [-0.26,1.32]), but not 10Hz rTMS (d=0.07, 95% CI [-0.85,0.71]), versus sham. Mentalizing-mirroring connectivity changes were negligible when comparing iTBS and 10Hz rTMS to sham. Pain scores were low (means < 5/10) and drop-out rates were consistent, across groups. Conclusions: This study marks the first investigation of individualized rTMS effects on social cognitive circuitry in SSDs, using the BOONStim pipeline. Our results suggest that iTBS can change mentalizing network connectivity, motivating an ongoing larger clinical trial using iTBS versus sham to assess changes in social cognitive performance. Funding Source: National Institute of Mental Health; Brain and Behavior Research Foundation Keywords: Repetitive Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (rTMS), Schizophrenia Spectrum Disorders, Social Cognition, Functional connectivity, Individualized Treatment
