N2  - Background: Cognitive remediation (CR) combined with transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) is effective in reducing cognitive decline in at-risk patients with remitted Major Depressive Disorder (rMDD) or Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI). We aimed to examine the moderating effects of baseline brain magnetic-resonance imaging (MRI) measures on the impact of CR+tDCS on longitudinal cognitive outcomes, and the effect of participant characteristics on this relationship. Methods: We analyzed data from the Prevention of Alzheimer’s dementia with CR and tDCS MCI and Depression (PACt-MD) randomized controlled trial in which 375 participants received CR+tDCS or sham CR+sham tDCS. In 246 participants (age: 71.9±6.15; 152 women) with a baseline scan, we assessed the moderating effect of fractional anisotropy (FA), overall cortical thickness (CT), and CT in Regions of Interest (ROI), including the medial temporal lobe, prefrontal cortex, and middle and inferior temporal region, on changes in global cognition, executive function, or verbal memory. Results: There were moderating effects of overall CT on change in global cognition (χ2=10.43, df=3, p=0.015) and of ROI CT on change both in executive function (χ2=11.57, df=3, p=0.009) and verbal memory (χ2=16.08, df=3, p=0.001). The difference in the decline in cognition with CR+tDCS vs. sham+sham was two to three times larger after three years in those with thick overall CT or ROI CT than in those with thin overall or ROI RCT. Conclusions: Global and regional CT could be used to select older adults at risk for dementia who are the most likely to benefit from CR+tDCS on slowing their cognitive decline. Funding Source: CGS-M Keywords: Geriatric Depression, Brain magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), Mild cognitive impairment, Alzheimer's Disease
