N2  - Background: Parkinson’s Disease (PD) has numerous outcomes for the patients, such as cognitive impairment, disabilities, depression, hospital admissions and mortality. The use of Deep Brain Stimulation (DBS) is a surgical approach that can help ease motor symptoms and decrease the use of medication in the selected patients. However, not all patients are eligible for DBS. If DBS is used earlier, the cost of medications can be reduced long-term, and patients will have slower disease progression. Methods: We analyzed a published retrospective evaluation of clinical files of patients with PD who underwent DBS surgery in a reference Center in Porto, Portugal, from 2002 to May 2019 and we conducted a further systematic review in PubMed using the following descriptors: ("Parkinson’s disease" AND "deep brain stimulation") AND ("long term mortality" OR "outcomes" OR "medication costs"), selecting articles published in the last 5 years, abstract, full text, and randomized controlled trial. Out of 25 studies, 3 were selected. Results: Two randomized controlled trials were conducted, with 265 patients (men and women). Compared to high frequency stimulation and better medical treatment, an improvement in dynamic postural stability and significant increase in UPDRS motor score was observed. The evaluation of clinical files from the reference center stated patients with longer disease duration had higher mortality rather than older patients at the time of surgery. Patients who underwent earlier DBS surgery also showed medication cost savings of $28.246 at 5 years and $104.958 at 15 years post-operatively. Conclusions: DBS surgery in patients with shorter disease duration provides long-term motor benefits, longer survival rate and long-term medication cost offset compared to standard medical care.
