N2  - Background: Huntington disease (HD) is a neurodegenerative disease resulting in motor and functional decline. Physical activity (PA) is a modifiable factor that improves motor function and quality of life in people with HD (PwHD). However, there is limited understanding about relationships between lifestyle PA, disease severity, and capacity measures. Baseline data from PACE-HD, a trial-within-cohort study, included measures of PA, physical capacity, and disease severity in PwHD. This secondary analysis evaluated the relationship of these measures across disease stages. Methods: We evaluated total functional capacity (TFC), total motor score (TMS), predicted VO2-max, 30s chair rise (30sCR), and self-reported PA (Brunel Lifestyle PA Questionnaire Planned (Brunel-P) and Unplanned (Brunel-U), International PA Questionnaire (IPAQ)). HD-ISS (0/1-5) stages were retrospectively assigned. Spearman correlations were performed to examine relationships. Results: In the sample (n=84), correlations between Brunel-U and TUG (r=-0.254; p=0.016) and Brunel-U and TFC (r=0.274; p=0.004) were small. In HD-ISS-2 (n=32), there was moderate correlation between Brunel-U and TUG (r=-0.405; p=0.049), and Brunel-U and 30sCR (r=0.426; p=0.038). In HD-ISS-3 (n=24), TMS had moderate correlation with Brunel-U (r=0.406, p<0.05). In late stages (HD-ISS-4/5 (n=53)) IPAQ and Brunel-P had moderate correlations with VO2-max (r=0.342, p<0.05 and r=0.319, p<0.05, respectively). Conclusions: Our findings show a relationship between engagement in unplanned PA and capacity, especially in HD-ISS-2, before functional decline, and HD-ISS-3, at the beginning of decline. In later HD, with more severe functional changes, VO2-max is related to planned PA. Although moderate-to-vigorous exercise is recommended for health benefits, our findings show daily physical activity (ex. climbing stairs) may be important for capacity and disease severity.
