N2  - Background: Huntington's disease (HD) is a genetic neurodegenerative condition leading to progressive deterioration in motor, cognitive, and behavioral function. PACE-HD, a therapist-mediated physical activity (PA) coaching intervention for people with HD (PwHD), involved an observational cohort (OC) of PwHD with nested randomized controlled trial (RCT). OC was assessed at baseline and 12 months with no contact points in between, making them ideal for studying HD’s natural history. This study aimed to examine changes in physiological, functional capacity, PA measures, and clinical rating scales among OC to determine which measures are sensitive to disease progression among PwHD. Methods: 58 PwHD (33M/25F; age (yrs):52.79± 11.09; TFC: 10.42 ± 2.26) were assessed at baseline and 12 months. Outcomes included VO2max, six-minute walk test (6MWT), Timed-up and-Go test (TUG), self-reported physical activity (PA) measures, namely, Brunel Lifestyle Physical Activity Questionnaire (Brunel) and International Physical Activity Questionnaire (IPAQ), Unified Huntington's disease rating scale (UHDRS) components including Total Motor Score (TMS) and Total Functional Capacity (TFC), HD-specific, patient-reported outcome (PRO) instrument of HD symptom (HD-PRO-TRIAD). Mean differences (MD) with 95% confidence interval (95%CI) were calculated, and paired t-test analysis was used to compare baseline with 12-month scores. Results: PwHD showed deterioration in clinically administered physiological (VO2max (MD: -194.19 ml.min-1, 95%CI: -335.95, -52.43)), functional capacity (6MWT (MD: -58.43 m, 95%CI: -106.38, -10.48)), and clinical disease rating measures (TFC (MD: -1.00, 95%CI: -1.39, - 0.62). TMS declined on average 2.5 points (MD: 2.40, 95%CI: - 3.6, 8.4). TUG, self-reported PA, and QOL measures did not change over 12 months (p>0.05). Conclusions: VO2max and 6MWT deteriorated, while self-perceived PA and QOL remained unchanged in PwHD over 12 months. VO2max and 6MWT are potentially reliable outcome measures for HD, given their responsiveness to PA interventions as per the literature and sensitivity to changes in disease status.
