N2  - Background: Parkinson’s Disease (PD) is a neurodegenerative disorder primarily marked by motor symptoms, but cognitive decline can also occur as the disease progresses. Current treatments for People with Parkinson Disease (PwPD) have started to propose Dual Task (DT) training programs, which combine motor and cognitive rehabilitation, with encouraging results in terms of walking speed and balance. Starting from this assumption, we propose to associate DT treatment with transcranial direct current electrical stimulation (tDCS), a low-cost, non-invasive brain stimulation, that recent studies suggest could be an effective intervention for PwPD. Methods: We will evaluate clinical effects of this new therapeutic approach through a quadruple-blind Randomized Controlled Trial (RCT), enrolling 30 PwPD. Until now, we have enrolled 13 patients (3 dropped-out) that have been randomized into 2 groups, both groups performed activities in DT associated with real or sham tDCS, real group (RG) or sham group (SG). Each patient carried out 12 rehabilitation sessions (2/week) of 30 minutes. Each participant was assessed at the baseline (T0) and at the end of the 6-weeks treatment (T1) for disease severity (Unified Parkinson’s Disease Rating Scale-UPDRS) and executive function (neuropsychological battery test). PwPD performed Instrumented Time Up and Go (iTUG) single and dual task conditions (iTUG alone, iTUG motor, iTUG cognitive) and an EEG analysis was executed at T0 and T1. [Formula presented] Results: Six participants to RG [mean age 69,5 years (7,44) and mean PD duration 7,83 years (5,6)] and four to SG [mean age 70,75 years (3,09) and mean PD duration 9,5 years (3,62)] were included in on-going analysis. Results show that UPDRS, iTUG 180° turn duration, EEG and phonemic fluencies show an improvement trend. [Formula presented] [Formula presented] [Formula presented] Conclusions: Compared with tDCS sham, tDCS real seems to add advantages to PwPD. Future analysis should confirm these data and a larger sample size is warranted to draw further conclusions about our approach.
