N2  - Whereas received wisdom is that depression declines across age, there is growing evidence the oldest old (people aged 80+ years) have higher rates of depression than people in midlife and young old age. Yet this is the group that receives the least subsidised mental health services and the most antidepressant prescriptions in Australia. Treatment-resistant, or difficult-to treat, depression tends to increase across age. Studies (e.g. OPTIMUM study) using stepwise pharmacotherapy protocols show modest rates of remission in treatment-resistant, latelife depression (TRLLD) and involve potentially toxic psychotropics. While repetitive Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (rTMS) and ketamine are not associated with significant cognitive adverse events, the few randomised controlled trials (RCTs) involving these modalities show heterogenous outcomes. Electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) remains the most effective therapy for depression, although the five-year outcomes show moderate to high rates of relapse, cognitive impairment and death (e.g. MODECT Study). Current approaches to TRLLD are limited by their focus on the failure to respond to physical therapies, whereas social isolation and loneliness, chronic physical comorbidities, childhood trauma and emerging neurodegenerative disease are salient factors. There is ample evidence for the efficacy of psychotherapies in late life, and clinicians should also prescribe social and physical activity. Bipolar disorders in older people have been traditionally neglected. While the multinational Global Ageing and Geriatric Experiments in Bipolar Disorder (GAGE-BD) consortium has produced better quality data, many participants are people in late middle age. There is one high-quality RCT comparing lithium and sodium valproate in acute mania, and evidence that the former reduces the risk of dementia in people with bipolar disorder.
