N2  - Introduction: Roughly one third of individuals who sustain a concussion will meet criteria for persistent post-concussion symptoms (PPCS) one-month post-injury. Cognitive dysfunction is experienced chronically by up to half of individuals after a single concussion. Unfortunately, there are few evidence-based treatments for PPCS and as such, neuromodulation approaches including repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) are being investigated. Objectives: To determine whether an rTMS protocol improves cognitive dysfunction (measured by the Saint Louis University Mental Status Examination (SLUMS)) associated with PPCS. Patients & methods: In an ongoing randomized double-blind sham-controlled clinical trial, 64 participants were randomized to 20 sessions over four weeks of high frequency (10Hz) rTMS (n=32) or sham rTMS (n=32). The rTMS protocol consisted of 10 trains of 60 pulses per session delivered to the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex at 100-120% of resting motor threshold. The SLUMS was administered at pre-treatment, post-treatment, 1-month and 3-month follow-up. A linear mixed effects model was used to examine the effects of time and condition on total SLUMS score. Results: Total SLUMS scores indicate 18/64 participants presented with mild cognitive dysfunction (score of ≤ 26) at pre-treatment. A significant main effect of time (β=-1.38,95%CI[-2.18,-0.57],p<.001) was observed over the intervention. Pairwise comparisons revealed significant improvement in SLUMS score compared to pre-treatment for all timepoints. A significant main effect of condition (β=- 0.66,95%CI[-1.17,-0.15],p=.012) was observed favoring rTMS compared to sham rTMS. There was no significant interaction effect between timepoint and condition. Conclusion: rTMS may be a promising treatment for cognitive dysfunction in PPCS. However, given the SLUMS is a screening tool, future research should replicate the study design using a more comprehensive cognitive assessment.
