N2  - Introduction: In patients with mild cognitive impairment (MCI), deficits in social cognition (SC) contribute to the risk of progressing to dementia. However, there are few pharmacological treatments to mitigate these abnormalities; therefore, alternative therapeutic approaches should be explored. Objectives: To assess short-/long-term effects of repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) on SC abilities in MCI patients by stimulating two sites belonging to the social brain and investigate whether the effect extends to other cognitive abilities supported by the stimulated network. Patients & methods: Eighteen MCI patients were randomized in two study groups. A multiple-baseline design was used; 4-weeks of real rTMS stimulation protocol was carried out by one group (RR-Gr), while 2-weeks of placebo treatment and 2 weeks of real rTMS stimulation by the other group (SR-Gr). Highfrequency neuronavigation-guided rTMS over medial prefrontal cortex (mPFC) and right temporoparietal junction (rTPJ) took place daily, 5 times a week. Improvement in SC performance was assessed at 2 (T2) and 4 (T4) weeks after rTMS, and 8 (T12) weeks after the end of rTMS. The following effects were investigated: short (baseline vs T2), long-lasting (baseline vs T4), maintenance (T12 vs T4), and overall treatment effects. Results: RR-Gr, compared to SR-Gr, showed improvements in theory of mind and empathy performances (p=0.01; p=0.03) at T2; in empathy performance (p=0.04) at T4; and in face emotion recognition (p=0.01) at T12. They also exhibited a positive overall treatment effect on complex mental representation (p=0.03) and social behaviour (p=0.01) over time. In both groups, rTMS had short and long-lasting effects on global cognitive abilities (p=0.02), mainly on fronto-executive function (p=0.03). Conclusions: Long-term rTMS treatment on two social brain areas contributes to improve and maintain complex SC abilities in MCI patients.
