N2  - Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) improves cognition in Alzheimer’s disease (AD), yet its biomarker and neuroplasticity effects remain unclear. Cognitive scale scores, plasma biomarker levels, and resting-state fMRI brain network in AD patients were analyzed before and after a 14-day 20 Hz rTMS intervention. The results demonstrated that rTMS intervention significantly improved cognitive performance (MMSE: Z = − 2.863, q = 0.017; MoCA: t = − 6.137, q < 0.001; RAVLT_I: t = − 3.436, q = 0.011) and reduced neuropsychiatric symptoms (NPI: Z = − 2.547, q = 0.037; HAMD: Z = − 3.472, q = 0.009). A 9.4% reduction in neurofilament light chain levels was demonstrated (Z = − 2.371, P = 0.018), with baseline p-Tau181 levels being inversely correlated to Aβ42 changes (R = − 0.428, P = 0.033). Enhanced global efficiency (GE: t = − 1.865, P = 0.081, r = 0.423) and increased connection density (CD: Z = − 1.823, P = 0.068, r = 0.442) were identified in neural networks. Notably, GE improvements positively correlated with elevated Aβ42/40 (R = 0.596, P = 0.025), while cognitive gains measured by the MoCA were significantly associated with network reorganization metrics (GE: R = 0.486, P = 0.048; CD: R = 0.514, P = 0.035). rTMS demonstrates potential in mitigating neurodegeneration by enhancing brain network integration and modulating Aβ metabolism. This effect was particularly pronounced in early-stage AD patients who exhibit preserved neural integrity. These findings advance therapeutic assessment frameworks and decode TMS neuromodulation mechanisms. The trial was prospectively registered (ChiCTR2400080657, ClinicalTrials.gov; 2024–02-04).
