N2  - Introduction and Discussion: Non-pharmacologic interventions (NPI) are increasingly recognized for their efficacy mitigating cognitive, emotional, motor, and functional deficits associated with Alzheimer’s disease and related dementias (ADRD). High definition transcranial direct current stimulation (HD-tDCS) provides a mechanism for directly altering regional and network level brain functioning using low levels of energy and is therefore well positioned to translate decades of observational neuroimaging research into a symptom specific intervention. This session focuses on key factors needed to establish HD-tDCS as a treatment for those with ADRD. Given the presumed link between symptoms (e.g., cognitive impairment) and brain activity, I will use data from case series and randomized-controlled trials to demonstrate the physiological effects of HD-tDCS in non-motor regions. However, we may need to reconsider existing dosing methods to consistently achieve such effects and mitigate clinical symptoms. I will highlight some key limitations as well as potential methods to overcome these limitations, including providing higher per-electrode (e.g., 4 mA) and total current (e.g., 10+ mA) amplitudes that are supported by safety and tolerability data. Finally, the availability and sustainability of any treatment is critical, so I will provide an overview of a novel method for the remote delivery of personalized HD-tDCS and show evidence supporting its acceptance in older adults with ADRD. Acknowledgements: Funding from the National Institute on Aging (R35AG072262, R01AG058724, P30AG053760) and the Department of Veterans Affairs (1I01RX001534) is also acknowledged. Financial Disclosures: Benjamin M. Hampstead licensed personalized neuromodulation headgear to Soterix Medical, Inc and may receive royalties from sales. Benjamin M. Hampstead receives book royalities from Oxford University Press
