N2  - Introduction: Aging presents numerous biological, cognitive, and physical challenges. By 2050, nearly 2 billion individuals will be over 60 years old (WHO, 2018). Aging is accompanied by cognitive declines, with research indicating an average 10% drop in episodic memory functions each decade after the age of 40 years (Hedden & Gabrieli, 2004). Moreover, aging leads to structural and functional brain changes, including reductions in gray matter volume and cortical thinning (Fjell & Walhovd, 2010). Mindfulness-based interventions have shown promise in mitigating certain aging effects on the brain. Several studies have observed increases in gray matter density in attention and emotion-regulation areas after 8-week meditation programs (Hölzel et al., 2011). Physical exercise, on the other hand, has been linked to an increase in hippocampal volume in older adults, which is crucial for memory (Erickson et al., 2011). Transcranial electrical stimulation (tDCS) has demonstrated potential in modulating neural activity and strengthening brain networks. Integrating these interventions could provide a synergistic approach, targeting multiple facets of age-related decline. While each intervention has distinct benefits, a comprehensive approach, similar to the FINGER project focusing on preventing cognitive decline (Ngandu et al., 2015), might address aging more holistically. This RCT protocol seeks to explore this synergy, offering insights into combined strategy implementations for intervention programs. The aim of the study is to assess the combined impact of tDCS, mindfulness, and physical exercise on the brain connectivity of older adults using functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI). It will also evaluate the effects on physical and cognitive functionality. Materials / Methods: Double-blind, randomized controlled2x2 trial with four intervention-groups: tDCS placebo; Active-tDCS only; Physical exercise and Jon Kabat-Zinn's Mindfulness-Based Stress Reduction (MBSR) program; Active-tDCS combined with physical exercise and MBSR. Participants: Aged ≥ 60 years, not diagnosed with dementia, lacking significant neurological or psychiatric disorders. Intervention: 8-week treatment combining MBSR and physical exercise with multifocal anodal-tDCS (1mA, 20 min), administered once weekly over dorsolateral Prefrontal Cortex and Primary Motor Cortex. Results: Outcome measures will be occur before the intervention (t0), post-intervention (t1) and at a six months follow-up (t2) to assess the impact of intervention on neuroconnectivity (fMRI); physical (10-Meter Walking Test; Chair Stand Test) and cognitive performance (neuropsychological battery-NEUROPSI). Discussion: The results will offer evidence regarding the possible efficacy of tDCS (combined with mindfulness and physical exercise) as a preventive strategy for physical or cognitive decline. Conclusions: The study might illuminate possible correlations between brain connectivity shifts and enhancements in physical and cognitive functionality. Financial Disclosures: No significant relationships Disclosure: No significant relationships.
