N2  - Introduction: Bipolar affective disorder is a chronic illness characterized by episodes of hypomania, maniaand depression. Patients with BD spend most of their time in depressive episodes and up to one-third of patients do not respond to adequate doses of medications. Although no consensus exists for definition of treatment-resistant bipolar depression (TRBD), failure of symptoms improvement despite an adequate trial of two therapeutic agents is a common theme of TRBD. A high prevalence of psychiatric and medical comorbidities is typical in affected individuals. Disorders such as hypersexuality, substance use or disability, especially in the manic phase, pose a high risk for the transmission of infections such as HIV. Recent research suggests the potential benefit of TMS for cognition in bipolar disorder patients. Materials / Methods: We performed a review of the published literature on the subject using PubMed. We conducted a search using ‘TMS’ ‘neuromodulation’ ‘bipolar affective disorder’ ‘hiv and bipolar affective disorder’. Results: TMS can be used to reduce neuroinflammation while not avoiding drug interactions in the treatment of depressive episodes, but also neuroinflammation in HIV-infected patients. Discussion: According to many guidelines, TMS treatment comes to the fore in treatment-resistant cases. Our patient suffered treatment resistans bipolar depression. It's recommended to take consideration of the kidney and hepatic functions while using antiretroviral treatments. Therefore, we predicted that the patient's kidney functions may be impaired by antiretroviral therapy. Also our patient was in great affliction about impaired cognitive functions. TMS could be good choice for elderly patient like this patient, whose GFR values tend to regress. Major depression in HIV patients has been linked to reduced white matter in the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex, anterior cingulate, left lateral occipitotemporal region, parietal lobe, and parahippocampal gyrus. rTMS has been shown in previous studies to improve cognitive functions and to have antidepressant properties. Conclusions: Bipolar disorder and HIV infection coexist at rates much higher than expected in the general population. The prevalence of HIV is particularly high among people with bipolar disorder, perhaps approaching 10%. Similarly, the prevalence of GH in HIV-infected individuals ranges from 2.6% to 9.1%. Previous studies have demonstrated the potential contribution of TMS treatment to cognitive function in bipolar patients. Neuropsychiatric effects of antiretroviral drugs used in HIV infection and interactions of antiretroviral drugs with psychotropics highlight the use of TMS in the treatment of bipolar affective disorder. Financial Disclosures: The authors did not receive support from any organization for the submitted work. Disclosure: No significant relationships.
