N2  - Introduction: A library of Virtual Reality (VR) tasks has been developed for targeted post-stroke distal upper-limb rehabilitation[1]. This study aims to evaluate its clinical impact as well as to explore neuroplastic changes induced in terms of cortical-excitability in comparison to dose-matched conventional rehabilitation. Materials / Methods: This is a pilot prospective study at clinical-settings including chronic stroke-survivors. Patients were randomly assigned to receive 20 therapy-sessions of 45min each, in VR-therapy Group (VRG)(n=8) and Conventional-rehabilitation Group (CG)(n=8). Clinical Scales, cortical-excitability measures (using single-pulse Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation): Resting Motor Threshold (RMT), and Motor Evoked Potential(MEP)-amplitude from EDC-muscle at pre- and post-therapy were acquired to evaluate therapy-induced improvements. Task-performance metrics i.e., Time to complete the task (TCT), trajectory smoothness, relative error and trajectory plots were evaluated for each VR-session. Results: There were no significant differences (p>0.05) between the demographic-characteristics in CG and VRG at pre-therapy. VRG evidenced significant (p<0.05) reduction in MAS-score (1.3±0.3 to 0.8±0.5), significant increment in FMA-UE score (from 43.3±9.4 to 49.8±9.4), wrist active range of motion (from 36.2º±14.8º to 46.8º±13.1º), and MBI-score (from 88.7±5.8 to 95.7±4.4) as compared to CG (MAS from 1.6±0.4 to 1.5±0.4, FMA-UE from 37.2±10.1 to 42.1±11.6, wrist AROM from 27.5º±11.6º to 35.6º±14.2º and MBI from 80.6±10.5 to 84.6±8.6) at post-therapy (Figure1). VRG demonstrated significant (p<0.05) improvement in cortical-excitability for ipsilesional-hemisphere in terms of decreased RMT(in%) (VRG: 69.2±15.4 to 60.7±15.5; CG: 68.6±18.9 to 66.2±15.6) and increased MEP-amplitude(in μVolt) (for VRG: 76.1±16.4 to 105.7±36.5; for CG: 79.6±62.4 to 81.9±59.8) as compared to CG at post-therapy. At post-therapy, TCT(in%) (from 96.8±9.3 to 72.3±13.2), trajectory smoothness (from 2755±883 to 1041±417) and relative error(in%) (from 42.5±14.2 to 10.5±4.8) significantly reduced for patients in VRG, and came in closer range of the reference values of these parameters (Figure2), same established in our earlier study[1]. Trajectory of a patient at day20 was observed similar to that of a representative healthy subject (Figure 3). Discussion: Repetitive distal-joint targeted VR-training demonstrated significant reduction in wrist spasticity (MAS), improved motor functionality (FMA-UE), and ADL-independence (AROM and MBI) as compared to CG at post-therapy. Neurophysiological changes observed in VRG in terms of improved cortical-excitability might be a consequence of practice-dependent plastic reorganization induced by VR-therapy. The task-performance as evaluated at day20 of VR-training was improved as compared to that of day1. Conclusions: VR-training exhibited improved motor outcomes and cortical-excitability in chronic stroke-survivors as compared to conventional rehabilitation. The outcomes encourage to further conduct a clinical trial with large patient-cohort to evaluate its actual clinical-potential. Supplemental Data: Patient Recruitment: All patients were recruited from the out-patient clinic of Department of Neurology, AIIMS, New Delhi. Patients were enrolled based on the inclusion criteria: age 18–75 years, having ischemic / hemorrhagic stroke, Mini-Mental Scale (MMSE) ≥ 24; Modified Ashworth Scale (MAS) = 0, 1, 1+, 2 at wrist and Brunnstrom Stage (BS) = 3–5. Patients with contra-indication to Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) and having any other progressive neurological or cognitive disorders were excluded from the study. All patients provided a written informed consent before enrolment in this study. Once enrolled, patients were then randomized into two groups: Conventional therapy Group (CG) and VR-therapy Group (VRG). Randomization procedure was conducted using opaque envelopes consisting of coloured cards indicating pre-defined sequence of groups to be allocated. Conventional Therapy: The CG received 45 min per day for 20 therapy sessions (5 days a week for 4 weeks) of conventional physiotherapy training. The type of activity, intensity, and frequency of protocol for CG was based on the baseline clinical presentation of the patient as reflected by clinical scales. The training consists of various tasks such as active-assisted shoulder/elbow/wrist activity, forearm pronation/supination, wrist flexor stretching, finger-opposition etc. Task challenges were introduced progressively, incorporating gradations from gross to fine movements, single to dual activities, non-weighted to weighted exercises etc. VR Therapy: A library of target-based non-immersive VR-tasks have been developed and standardized in our previous work for the distal upper-extremities in a cohort of healthy subjects and two patients with stroke [1]. A joystick (Logitech Extreme 3D Pro®, Lausanne, Switzerland) interface was used to translate and map the hand motions into the created environment. The joystick facilitates movement of the wrist with a flexion/extension and radial/ulnar deviation motion with ±15 degrees of yaw and pitch angle respectively from its mean position. The joystick facilitates diferent wrist and finger movements such as: wrist flexion/extension, wrist ulnar/radial deviations, index finger flexion/extension and thumb with abduction/adduction. The VR-task consists of a target presented in the form of a 3D duck model. Different 3D objects in the form of obstacles are present on the driving path. Pitch movements of the joystick move the car in forward/backward direction, while the yaw movements of the joystick drive the car in left/right direction. In some of the tasks, the user has to press a specific button using thumb or index finger as instructed to remove a specific obstacle from the trajectory path. The goal of the subject was to reach a pre-defined target-position within a specified time-bound, while travelling through a track with various obstacles (standardized in [1]). The difficulty of the task levels is graded in terms of parameters such as number of obstacles, specified time-limit, shape of the trajectory path and the combinations of finger and wrist movements required to execute.A collision with the obstacles during the process will result in a notification with audio-visual feedback to the subject. The task GUI consists of the instruction panel, score, timer, top-view window and the performance-based feedback to the user. Each subject was given the VR-therapy for 20 sessions (one session/day for 5 days/week for 4 weeks) of 45-minutes time during each session, with extra up to maximum 15-minutes (three times each consisting of 5 minutes) of rest-period in between if required. All sessions were performed under the supervision of an experienced physiotherapist. Patients were asked to comfortably sit straight in a chair and place their arm on the table with the elbow ∼100-120 degrees. A chair and table both having adjustable height are used to match the joystick position with the height of the patient’s arm in a comfortable sitting position. Patients were instructed to perform the joystick movements using only their impaired wrist and fingers. While performing joystick movements, the patients were continuously monitored and instructed to restrict the proximal movements as much as possible. None of the patients in VRG had any earlier exposure to VR-sessions and hence a practice session of 15 minutes was provided at the beginning using their unaffected hands to make them familiar with the protocol. After the practice session, patients were asked to perform the VR-tasks using their affected hands. Appropriate rest period was provided whenever the patient feels uncomfortable during the sessions. Acknowledgements: This research work was supported by Indian Council of Medical Research (ICMR) of theGovernment of India (55/4/1/CARE-Disability & AT/2020/NCD-II) and Abdul Kalam Technology Innovation National Fellowship by Indian National Academy of Engineering (INAE/121/AKF/38). Financial Disclosures: No significant relationships Disclosure: No significant relationships.
