N2  - Symposium title Efficacy and Hemodynamic Responses of Electrical and Magnetic Brain Stimulation in Alzheimer’s Treatment Abstract We investigated the effect of transcranial alternating current stimulation (tACS) as a treatment Alzheimer's disease (AD) repeatedly over three years. The protocol for each block of treatment was applying tACS at 40 Hz paired with simultaneous tutored cognitive training (using MindTriggers app) in two 30-min sessions/day, 5 days/week for 4 weeks. There was 3-6 months washout period between each two blocks of treatment. This protocol was applied to 12 patients (4 females) with AD for up to 6 blocks of treatment over three years. The anode electrode of tACS was placed on the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex and cathode on the contralateral supraorbital area of the brain with 0.75 mA p-p amplitude. We assessed the participants with Wechsler Memory Scale (WMS-IV) at pre and post of each treatment block. Out of the 12 participants, 7 received only two blocks of treatment and the rest received 5 and 6 blocks of treatment over a period of 3 years. Due to COVID19 Pandemic, 6 blocks of treatment for three participants were done by only cognitive exercises (no tACS) remotely through video call. We calculated the changes in WMS score in each assessment with respect to the initial baseline and normalized it by dividing the change to the score at the initial baseline in order to average between the participants. The results show a sinusoidal pattern, with patients improving by 20% after each treatment block, followed by a decline during the time to next treatment block. On average the cognitive status of participants remained stable or slightly improved over 3 years. Given the expected rapid decline in patients with AD, these results are very encouraging and suggest that tACS combined with cognitive exercise may help maintain cognitive stability in patients with AD. Research Category and Technology and Methods Translational Research: 8. Transcranial Alternating Current Stimulation (tACS) Keywords tACS, repeated treatment, cognitive training, Alzheimer's disease
