N2  - Symposium title Efficacy and hemodynamic responses of electrical and magnetic stimulation in Alzheimer’s treatment Abstract Rational: Our recent large-scale clinical trial investigating the efficacy of repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) for Alzheimer’s disease (AD) reported significant cognitive improvement for both sham and active rTMS; the sham coil was found to generate up to 25% intensity of the active coil. In this study, we aimed to investigate the immediate effects of single-session rTMS at different intensities on brain hemodynamic activities in healthy volunteers and patients with AD using functional near infrared spectroscopy (fNIRS), which is a noninvasive brain imaging technique that measures oxygenated hemoglobin (HbO) concentration changes in the cerebral cortex. Methods: Eight Healthy volunteers (3 males, 53.9±21.6 years) and seven individuals with AD (6 males, 74.4±7.3 years) received 150 active rTMS pulses at 25% and 100% of their resting motor threshold (RMT), and sham rTMS at 100% RMT; each on a separate day in a randomized order. The pulses were delivered to the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) at 20 Hz in 1.5 sec trains with 10 sec intertrain interval. fNIRS recordings were performed before and immediately after rTMS, during a subtraction task. Results: Overall, both groups showed significant increases in HbO on the left DLPFC after the active rTMS at 100% intensity. After active rTMS stimulation at 25% intensity, only the AD group showed a significant decrease in the HbO level of the left DLPFC. No significant changes in the HbO response were observed after sham stimulation in either group. Conclusion: Our findings suggest single-session active rTMS has immediate intensity-dependent effects on cognitive task performance and the brain hemodynamic responses. The observed different patterns of HbO between healthy and AD groups may reflect distinct neurovascular mechanisms underlying rTMS effects. However, these results should be verified in a larger population. Research Category and Technology and Methods Translational Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords TMS, fNIRS, hemodynamic response, Alzheimer's disease
