N2  - Symposium title Advancing non-invasive brain stimulation in geriatric mental health Abstract Background: Advanced dementia (AD) with severe agitation and aggression profoundly impacts the quality of life for patients and caregivers and presents substantial clinical management challenges. For individuals who have not responded to psychotropic medications and behavioral interventions, electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) may be a viable treatment option. The ECT-AD trial, funded by the National Institute on Aging, aims to evaluate the effectiveness of ECT in this population. This presentation will review the literature supporting the trial, scientific rationale and study design, and the rationale for right unilateral lead placement. Baseline patient characteristics, ECT parameters, and trial progress will be discussed. Methods: Baseline assessments included cognitive function (Mini-Mental State Examination [MMSE], Severe Impairment Battery [SIB-8]), functional impairment (Barthel Index [BI]), and agitation (Cohen-Mansfield Agitation Inventory [CMAI], Neuropsychiatric Inventory [NPI], Pittsburgh Agitation Scale [PAS]). ECT parameters at baseline include number of stimulations, energy dose, charge, and seizure duration. Results: There are 27 participants enrolled to date (mean age 72.9, 55.6% male), 81.5% were White, 11.1% African American, 3.7% Asian, and 7.4% Hispanic/Latino. Dementia subtypes are Alzheimer’s (70.4%), vascular dementia (22.2%), frontotemporal dementia (3.7%) and Lewy body dementia (3.7%). At baseline, participants exhibited cognitive (MMSE 4.1±5.4, SIB-8 3.7±4.48) and functional (BI 47.2±21.1) impairments, and severe agitation and aggression (CMAI 77.8± 0.9, NPI agitation 15.4±6.5, NPI aggression 10.1±5.9, PAS 7.7±4.4). ECT data were available for 18 patients, with the first session involving 1.4±0.9 stimulations, mean 7.9±5.3 % energy, and 37.4±26.0 mC. Seizure durations were 36.9±19.8 (motor) and 46.1±25.5 (central), indicating adequate seizure duration. Conclusions: Baseline data from the ECT-AD trial highlight the severe impairments and agitation in this advanced dementia cohort. The observed seizure durations during ECT suggest its potential effectiveness in managing treatment-refractory agitation, offering a promising therapeutic option in this challenging population. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 2. Electroconvulsive Therapy (ECT) Keywords late-stage dementia, behavioral disturbances, neuropsychiatric symptoms
