N2  - Abstract Background: Intermittent theta-burst stimulation (iTBS) targeting the dorsomedial prefrontal cortex (DMPFC) is a promising intervention for treatment-resistant depression (TRD). However, its full therapeutic potential remains underexplored, especially when considering personalized functional circuit targeting and dose optimization. Objective: To assess the efficacy and safety of circuit-based, high-dose iTBS targeting the DMPFC in patients with TRD. Methods: A randomized, sham-controlled, double-blind trial was conducted at the Hebei Provincial Mental Health Center, enrolled patients with TRD aged 18 to 65 years, currently experiencing moderate to severe depressive episodes. The treatment target was individualized using a personalized brain function sectors (pBFS) approach, which identified regions within the default-mode circuit in the DMPFC based on a 30-minute resting-state functional MRI. Participants were randomly assigned in a 2:1 ratio to receive active or sham iTBS treatment, consisting of 10 sessions with 18000 pulses daily over 5 consecutive days. Follow-up assessments were conducted at 2 and 4 weeks post-treatment, with no changes to medications throughout the study. The efficacy outcome was the remission rate, defined as a Montgomery-Åsberg Depression Rating Scale (MADRS) score below 11. Results: Of the 45 randomized participants (mean age, 38.84 years, 68.18% female), 44 completed the treatment and follow-up (active group: n = 29; sham group: n = 15). The remission rates in the active group were 3.45% (vs. 13.33%, p = 0.218) immediately after treatment and 58.62% (vs. 26.67%, p = 0.044) at any follow-up point within 4 weeks post-treatment. While the immediate antidepressant effects were modest, they became more pronounced over time, resulting in significant symptom relief within the 4-week period post-treatment. The treatment was well-tolerated, with no cognitive deficit or adverse events reported. Conclusions: High-dose iTBS targeting the connectivity-guided DMPFC is a safe and potentially effective treatment for TRD, with therapeutic benefits increasing over time. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords Treatment-resistant depression, Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation, Dorsomedial prefrontal cortex, Double-blind randomized controlled trial
