N2  - Abstract Background: Brain-derived neurotrophic factor (BDNF) has been investigated as a potential biomarker of treatment response for the treatment of depression with repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS). rTMS is also used to treat cognitive impairments resulting from traumatic brain injury (TBI). However, biological factors underlying treatment response in TBI are not well understood. BDNF plays a role in neuroplasticity and in the connectivity of neural networks, which in depression exhibit both hypo and hyperconnectivity within the default mode network (DMN). Here we test the relationship between BDNF levels and DMN connectivity in a double-blind randomized trial using rTMS in Veterans with TBI. Secondarily, we will also investigate the relationship between DTI changes and BDNF levels. Methods: Twenty-four Veterans (21 men) with TBI were enrolled in treatment (n = 11) or sham (n = 10) at VA Palo Alto. FDA approved rTMS parameters were used (10 Hz stimulation at left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex). Blood samples and MRIs were collected at baseline (T0) and post treatment (T20). We also obtained resting state DTI measures. Results: Treatment did not significantly change BDNF levels (Active: -0.31±3.02; Sham: 0.25±3.10) or DMN connectivity (Active: -0.35±2.15; Sham: -1.64±1.46; p>0.1). BDNF change was significantly correlated with DMN connectivity (p<.0211). When DMN at T20 was the outcome, there were no significant effects of BDNF change, at baseline DMN in Treatment/Sham (p> 0.1). We will also report on preliminary relationships between changes in BDNF and changes in DTI measures. Conclusions: Results show a correlation between BDNF change and DMN connectivity where higher BDNF levels are associated with lower DMN connectivity – an indicator of improved brain function. This association is not driven by rTMS treatment. Research Category and Technology and Methods Translational Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords TBI, TMS, DTI
