N2  - Symposium title Noninvasive brain stimulation techniques in Alzheimer's disease 2.0 Abstract Objective: This study examines the efficacy and safety of transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) on cognitive function in individuals with mild cognitive impairment (MCI), Alzheimer’s disease (AD), and Alzheimer’s disease-related dementias (ADRD). Methods: A systematic review and meta-analysis was conducted. Searches were performed across MEDLINE, Embase, Cochrane Library, APA PsycINFO, Web of Science, and Scopus. Randomized controlled trials (RCTs), open-label trials, and case series reporting cognitive outcomes following TMS interventions in MCI, AD, and ADRD were included. Cognitive and safety outcomes were assessed, and study quality was evaluated using the Cochrane Risk of Bias tool for RCTs and the Methodological Index for Non-Randomized Studies (MINORS) criteria. The review protocol was registered with PROSPERO (CRD42022326423). Results: A total of 143 studies with a combined participant pool of 5,800 participants were included in the analysis, consisting of 94 randomized controlled trials, 46 open-label studies, and 3 case series. Meta-analysis of 25 RCTs involving MCI and AD populations demonstrated significant improvements in global cognitive measures, with large effect sizes observed for the Alzheimer’s Disease Assessment Scale-Cognitive subscale (SMD = -0.96 [-1.32, -0.60], p < 0.001), Montreal Cognitive Assessment (SMD = 0.85 [0.26, 1.44], p = 0.005), and Mini-Mental State Examination (SMD = 0.80 [0.26, 1.33], p = 0.003). There was significant heterogeneity across studies. There were four reported serious adverse events of seizures, of which 3 were deemed unrelated to TMS, and 1 was resolved by coil repositioning. Conclusion: TMS appears to be a promising and well-tolerated intervention for improving cognitive function in individuals with MCI, AD, and ADRD. The evidence suggests significant cognitive benefits with a low incidence of serious adverse events. Given the heterogeneity of study designs and TMS protocols across studies, further studies are needed to determine optimal stimulation parameters for those with cognitive impairment Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords cognition, dementia, non-AD, RCT
