N2  - Abstract Gamma-band activity (30-200 Hz) is tightly linked to brain functions such as memory, perception, or decision making often compromised across various brain disorders such as schizophrenia, Alzheimer’s, or Parkinson’s disease. While all these disorders show distinct gamma band abnormalities that could be targeted with brain stimulation, non-invasive, single-trial manipulation of gamma oscillations was regarded unfeasible because of stimulation artifacts and an insufficient signal-to-noise ratio for continuous phase tracking in non-invasive brain recording. Here, we overcame this limitation using a new generation of quantum sensors, and demonstrate single-trial, phase-dependent modulation of auditory loudness perception linked to gamma-band auditory steady-state responses (ASSRs) using amplitude-modulated transcranial alternating current stimulation (AM-tACS). ASSRs were recorded using optically pumped magnetometers (OPMs) placed over temporal brain regions across healthy volunteers. Using a linearly constrained minimum variance (LCMV) beamformer, we suppressed the electric stimulation artifact and reconstructed single-trial phase of the ASSR. We find that the phase difference between AM-tACS and reconstructed ASSR modulated loudness perception, demonstrating that phase-dependent neuromodulation of gamma-frequency brain oscillations is feasible. Besides representing a powerful tool to investigate the causal role of gamma band activity in the human brain, our results suggest potential therapeutic applications for disorders characterized by gamma-band abnormalities. Research Category and Technology and Methods Translational Research: 8. Transcranial Alternating Current Stimulation (tACS) Keywords Loudness perception, tACS, gamma-band, phase-dependent
