N2  - Abstract Background: Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) is a promising strategy for cognitive enhancement in patients with neurocognitive disorders. However, studies combining tDCS with cognitive training (CT) remains limited. This study outlines a protocol to evaluate the efficacy of tDCS-augmented CT in patients with mild cognitive impairment (MCI) and Alzheimer's disease (AD). Preliminary results from CT will also be presented. Methods: Our study will use a randomized, sham-controlled, double-blind clinical trial design. The planned sample size is 40 participants per group. Participants will be randomly assigned to CT with either active tDCS or sham tDCS group in a 1:1 ratio. They will receive one session per week for 10 weeks. The anode will be positioned over the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex and the cathode was placed in the right supraorbital area. A current of 2 mA will be administered for 30 minutes during concurrent CT in the active tDCS group. For CT, we will use a Multi-strategic Memory Training program, which consists of 10 sessions, each lasting 60 minutes. The Korean version of the the Consortium to Establish a Registry for Alzheimer’s disease (CERAD-K) neuropsychological battery will be assessed at baseline and at 12 weeks. The primary outcome measure will be the total score of the CERAD-K neuropsychological battery. Results: Three MCI and 2 AD patients were recruited, all of whom completed 10 sessions of CT. One MCI patient was excluded from the analysis due to withdrawal of consent. Preliminary analyses revealed CT has significant efficacy in improving general cognition and executive function. Specifically, the AD subgroup demonstrated significant enhancement in memory and general cognition, whereas the MCI subgroup showed no significant benefits from CT. Discussion: This study will provide an optimised protocol fot evaluating the effects of tDCS as an augmentation strategy in CT for patients with neurocognitive disorders. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 9. Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) Keywords tDCS, cognitive training, mild cognitive impairment, Alzheimer's disease
