N2  - Abstract Background: Transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) is an effective intervention for improving cognitive impairment in stroke patients, but its efficacy in the domains of cognition is inconsistent and has not been clearly established. This systematic review assessed the efficacy of TMS in improving executive function, attention, and memory in this population. Methods: We searched the indexed literature up to July 2024 to identify all randomised controlled trials (RCTs) of this effect in stroke patients in seven databases, including PubMed, Scopus, Cochrane Library, CINAHL, NeuroBITE, PEDro and OTseeker. This systematic review was conducted according to the Cochrane Library Handbook and PRISMA (preferred reporting items for systematic reviews and meta-analyses) guidelines, and the quality of the evidence was assessed using ROB2 tools. Meta-analyses were performed using the standardised mean difference (SMD) (Hedge's g) as the effect measure, and subgroup analyses were performed to explore potential outcomes. Results: Thirteen RCTs with 496 stroke patients were included. The results showed that TMS could affect executive function (6 RCTs with SMD = 0.55; 95% confidence interval (CI) [0.04; 1.05]) and memory (9 RCTs with SMD = 0.57; 95% CI [0.25; 0.89]) in patients with stroke. However, the effectiveness of TMS on attention (5 RCTs with SMD = 0.32; 95% CI [-0.1; 0.75]) was not clear. Conclusions: TMS may affect executive function and memory, but not attention. The quality of the evidence for the results was variable due to heterogeneity and bias, so the results should be considered with caution and more rigorous evidence is needed. Trial registration: (in PROSPERO) CRD42024549230 Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords transcranial magnetic stimulation, executive function, attention, memory
