N2  - Abstract Introduction: Post-COVID-19 syndrome often results in fatigue and cognitive deficits, mainly in attention, memory and executive functions, significantly affecting daily life for up to at least one year post-infection. Non-invasive neuromodulation, like transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS), is a promising approach to managing these symptoms. This study aims to evaluate the efficacy of tele-assisted remote tDCS for post-COVID-19 fatigue and cognitive deficits. Methods: A parallel, double-blind, randomized clinical trial is being conducted with thirty patients (15 control, 15 experimental; 50% women) experiencing cognitive deficits and fatigue following SARS-CoV-2 infection. Participants are recruited from the Hospital de Terrassa (Barcelona, Spain). Sociodemographic and clinical data are collected, and fatigue, emotion, cognition, and quality of life are evaluated at three time points: pre-intervention, post-intervention, and at a six-month follow-up. The treatment comprises a 20-session (4-week) intervention of bilateral tDCS, delivered at 2 mA for 20 minutes per session. The anode is positioned over the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC; F3), and the cathode is placed over the right supraorbital area. The first session takes place at the hospital to assess tolerability and ensure participants can self-administer the treatment. The subsequent eighteen sessions are performed remotely, once daily, with real-time professional videoconferencing supervision. The final session is completed in person in the hospital to evaluate treatment satisfaction, feasibility, and post-intervention outcomes. The control group undergoes an identical intervention but with sham tDCS. Expected results: tDCS has demonstrated effectiveness in reducing fatigue and cognitive impairments in different neurological and neuropsychiatric disorders. We expect to confirm the effectiveness of remote tDCS intervention in mitigating fatigue and cognitive deficits resulting from COVID-19. Additionally, given tDCS's safety, comfort, and portability, we expect patients will prefer this method over hospital-based treatments. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 9. Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) Keywords tDCS, Post-COVID syndrome, Cognition, Fatigue
