N2  - Symposium title New frontiers in the field of brain stimulation and substance use disorders Abstract Substance use disorders represents the pathological usurpation of anterior midcingulate cortex (MCC) that normally serves several goal-directed processes (e.g. action selection and control, reward valuation, decision-making). Our goal is to optimize a TMS intervention for the purpose of modulating the reward and control function of the MCC, as evaluated by two electrophysiological phenomena called the reward positivity (RewP) and frontal midline theta oscillations (FMT) respectively, in nicotine users. We systematically measured the efficacy of various image-based targeting techniques (fMRI, diffusion-weighted-imaging[DWI], resting-state functional-connectivity [RSFC], and cortical thickness) to modulate the RewP and FMT in 35 dependent smokers. Participants were randomly assigned to Active (n=17) or Sham (n=18) TMS. Four DLPFC targets were identified for each subject within a left DLPFC ‘mask’ and the coil angle based on simulated e-fields. Across two EEG-TMS sessions, a robotic arm positioned the TMS coil <1 cm over each Target in a randomized order, and a total of 1000 pulses was delivered and 200 T-maze reward trials completed for each target. Participants also completed a probabilistic selection task (PST) to measure post-TMS effects on feedback-related FMT. Overall, the Active TMS group displayed a larger RewP (2.33μV) compared to the Sham TMS group (.86 μV), p<.0001, with the DWI targeting displayed the largest effect size (Cohen’s d= 1.5). By contrast, the RSFC target had the largest effect size on FMT power (Cohen’s d= -.685) compared to other targets. Here, we provided compelling evidence that DWI targeting was the optimal protocol to boost the reward function of the MCC in nicotine users, and RSFC to boost the control function. We hope that our research can help reduce the frequency and severity of neurocognitive deficits among substance use disorders, which may ultimately increase substance users’ control over substance use and maintaining treatment goals. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords Anterior midcingulate cortex, Robot-guided TMS, Image-based targeting, addiction
