N2  - Abstract Objectives: To explore whether gamma frequency-transcranial Alternating Current Stimulation (tACS) effects differ in mild [Mini Mental State Examination (MMSE] score > 24) versus moderate (MMSE < 24) Alzheimer’s Disease (AD) patients. Materials and method: Twelve mild [6 females; age 73 ± 3.7; MMSE score 25.8 ± 2.0] and ten moderate (7 females; age 77 ± 6.9; MMSE score 23.1 ± 2.6) AD patients underwent a verbal memory task [Rey Auditory Verbal Learning Test (RAVLT)] before and after 60 minutes treatment with three different tACS protocols targeting the bilateral temporoparietal regions. Participants were randomized to receive: i) gamma-tACS (40 Hz), ii) alpha-tACS (10 Hz), iii) and sham. Five minutes, eyes closed, resting-state electroencephalographic recording was performed before and after each stimulation session. Results: A significant interaction between conditions and time was reported in moderate but not mild patients for both RAVLT immediate (F2,16= 4.29, p= 0.03) and delayed recall (F2,16= 5.23, p= 0.01). Post-hoc tests indicated that gamma-tACS post was significantly different from gamma-tACS pre (p= 0.02) and sham post (p= 0.04) for the immediate recall, and from gamma-tACS pre (p= 0.004), alpha-tACS post (p= 0.03), and sham post (p= 0.005) for the delayed recall, respectively. A significant modulation of pre- to post-gamma power after gamma-tACS was found in 4 electrodes (Cz, Pz, CP1, and P3) in moderate (t8= -2.75, p= 0.02) but not mild patients (t9= -1.85, p= 0.09).Alpha power modulation was found in both groups following alpha-tACS, but no significant changes were observed after sham stimulation. Discussion: We found a significant effect of gamma-tACS on memory performance and gamma power modulation in moderate but not mild AD patients. This suggests that the beneficial effects of gamma-tACS become evident during the moderate phase of the disease, when PV+ interneuron hypoactivation has already occurred. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 8. Transcranial Alternating Current Stimulation (tACS) Keywords Alzheimer’s Disease, Episodic Memory, gamma-tACS
