N2  - Symposium title Deep brain stimulation of the nucleus basalis of Meynert to improve executive function Abstract Deep brain stimulation (DBS) of the nucleus basalis of Meynert (NBM) has shown potential as a therapeutic approach for Alzheimer's disease (AD). Our phase I clinical trial confirmed that NBM DBS is safe and achieves cognitive outcomes comparable to traditional treatments. Preclinical studies suggest that intermittent DBS (iDBS) patterns may provide superior cognitive benefits compared to continuous stimulation. To explore this further, we investigated the effects of 1-hour daily iDBS on short-term memory in aged transgenic TgF344-AD rats. Stimulation was administered at 60 Hz, 100 μA, with a pulse width of 100 μs, and a duty cycle of 20 seconds ON/40 seconds OFF, targeting the dorsal NBM. Cognitive performance was assessed using the object location test (OLT) and object recognition test (ORT). Our results demonstrated a positive, gradual increase in the time spent exploring novel objects or locations, indicating significant improvements in short-term memory. Additionally, we evaluated the impact of two months of daily iDBS on AD pathology and the cholinergic system's integrity in the cortex. We observed reductions in amyloid plaque deposition and tau tangles, along with changes in cortical cholinergic markers, including increased expression of vesicular acetylcholine transporter (VAChT) and α7-nicotinic acetylcholine receptors. These findings suggest that iDBS not only improves cognitive function in aged transgenic animal models but also positively influences cholinergic system integrity and AD pathology. Our data support the potential of iDBS as a therapeutic strategy for enhancing cognitive function and modifying disease progression in AD. Research Category and Technology and Methods Translational Research: 1. Deep Brain Stimulation (DBS) Keywords nucleus basalis of Meynert, working memory, deep brain stimulation
