N2  - Abstract Using non-invasive brain stimulation (NIBS) technologies like transcranial alternating current stimulation (tACS) and transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) to entrain gamma frequency oscillations may offer potential treatment for Alzheimer's disease. We examined how NIBS protocols designed to induce and stabilize 40 Hz gamma oscillations affect functional connectivity in the human brain. Specifically, we explored the efficiency of information transfer across the entire brain (global efficiency) and the synchrony of oscillatory activity between different regions (Phase Locking Value). Five TMS-tACS protocols were implemented: (1) a customized 40-Hz intermittent theta burst stimulation (iTBS) with sham tACS, (2) a 40-Hz tACS protocol (1 mA peak-to-peak) with sham iTBS, (3-4) two iTBS protocols phase-locked to the peak or trough of the tACS (Peak/Trough X-tACS), and (5) a sham stimulation protocol. Functional connectivity was assessed through resting-state EEG, measured before and up to two hours after each intervention across five sessions. In all protocols, tACS electrodes and two TMS coils were placed on the left and right DLPFC, with a stimulation duration of 20 minutes. All active protocols significantly improved global efficiency at 30, 60, 90, and 120 minutes post-intervention compared to the sham condition in the eyes-open condition. tACS and iTBS showed stronger acute effects, while tACS and X-tACS-peak demonstrated more significant lasting effects. Regarding PLV, the X-tACS Peak protocol elevated gamma functional connectivity in the left frontotemporal regions, while the X-tACS Trough protocol decreased it in the same area and increased connectivity in the right frontotemporal regions, for up to 60 minutes post-intervention. In contrast, the tACS and iTBS protocols predominantly enhanced gamma band connectivity in the left frontotemporal areas during both eyes open and closed conditions for up to 30 minutes post-intervention. The results suggest effective changes in the functional connectivity patterns following different NIBS protocols targeting 40 Hz gamma oscillations Research Category and Technology and Methods Basic Research: 8. Transcranial Alternating Current Stimulation (tACS) Keywords gamma oscillation, transcranial alternating current stimulation, theta burst stimulation, Alzheimer's disease
