N2  - Symposium title tDCS and Cognitive Interventions: Randomized Controlled Trials Investigating their Synergy Abstract Alzheimer's disease (AD) currently has no treatments that can stop its progression. There is strong evidence indicating that older adults with remitted major depressive disorder (rMDD) and mild cognitive impairment (MCI) are at high risk of developing AD. This highlights the need for early interventions to prevent AD in these populations. Brain stimulation is a promising approach to enhance performance and prevent AD. One example is the "Preventing Alzheimer’s Dementia with Cognitive Remediation Plus Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation in Mild Cognitive Impairment and Depression" (PACt-MD) study (NCT02386670). PACt-MD was a double-blind randomized trial that investigated the efficacy of cognitive remediation with transcranial direct current stimulation (CR+tDCS) in preventing cognitive decline and AD in a cohort of 375 older adults with MCI, rMDD, and MCI+rMDD (mean±SD age of 72.2±6.4 years, 232 women). The study involved assessments at baseline, week 8, and annually, with a median follow-up of 48.3 months [range: 2.1–85.9]. PACt-MD found that CR+tDCS significantly slowed cognitive decline in the combined sample of MCI and rMDD participants (likelihood-ratio test: p=0.006). However, the mechanisms driving the efficacy in PACt-MD remain unknown, including whether tDCS individual current flow predicts response to the intervention. In PACt-MD, we positioned tDCS electrodes at Fz and Iz to maximize bilateral dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (dlPFC) activation. To assess the underlying mechanisms, we used current flow modeling with individual brain MRIs to measure the electrical field (EF) induced at the dlPFC and investigated its relationship with response to intervention using linear regression models. The findings will be presented. In conclusion, CR+tDCS effectively slows cognitive decline. Personalized current flow modeling in such a large and successful trial offers insights into the mechanisms of brain stimulation efficacy. This approach has the potential to lead to more targeted and effective interventions for preventing AD. Research Category and Technology and Methods Translational Research: 9. Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) Keywords tDCS, Current flow modeling, Alzheimer’s Disease, rMDD
