N2  - Abstract Background: Evidence suggests that a purposeful and satisfying life enhances resilience against both pathological and healthy aging (Boyle et al. Arch. Gen. Psych 2012; 69(5), 499–505; Abellaneda-Pérez et al. Alzh Res Ther 2019; Alzheimer's research & therapy, 15(1), 49). Neuroplasticity may be a key neurophysiological mechanism enabling the brain to adapt and resist negative impacts (Pascual-Leone & Bartrés-Faz. Ann Neurol 2021;90(3):336-349). This study investigated the relationship between plasticity mechanisms, life purpose and life satisfaction/well-being in cognitively preserved older adults. Methods: Twenty-eight cognitively preserved older adults (age: mean=74, SD=3.6, range=66-82) were included. All subjects fulfilled the Purpose in Life (PiL) questionnaire and the Cantril Self-Anchoring Striving Scale, for which two scores were derived: 'Current' and 'Expected' life satisfaction/well-being. Participants also completed in a randomized order two study sessions, each involving evaluation of modulation of cortical excitability by either real or sham intermittent theta burst (iTBS) to the left prefrontal cortex. Cortical excitability was measured at baseline, immediately after iTBS, and at 15- and 30-minutes post-stimulation using single-pulse transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) with concurrent electroencephalography (EEG). As proxies for plasticity, we assessed local and global evoked responses post-iTBS and expressed them as the normalized deviation relative to the pre-iTBS baseline. The focus was on EEG evoked response amplitudes between 15-40 ms post-iTBS, which may best reflect direct cortical pyramidal excitability. Results and discussion: Negative relationships between global evoked responses (plasticity) and PiL and Current-well-being, were significant after active iTBS but not after sham stimulation (Fig. 1). Present findings suggest that individuals with high rates of PiL and well-being are more resistant to externally induced changes/perturbations in cortical plasticity. Such findings may provide a causal mechanistic insight into the neural underpinnings of these psychological constructs. [Formula presented] Research Category and Technology and Methods Translational Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords Plasticity, Aging, Resilience, Psychological factors
