N2  - Abstract Dementia imposes significant disability and death worldwide. Our previous studies have demonstrated that tDCS can improve memory up to 380% in healthy young adults (Clark etal. 2012; Gibson etal. 2020). Here we used the same protocol to conduct a registered, randomized, double-blind clinical trial (NCT05077826) in 85 older adults, including healthy controls (HC) and patients with Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI) and early stage Alzheimer’s Disease (AD). Participants performed the PRETXT discovery learning task for one hour, categorizing street images without being given explicit clues how to solve the task. Anodal tDCS (2.0 mA) was applied for 30 minutes over the right temple (F10), with the cathode placed on the left arm. sMRI and fMRI were collected before and after stimulation. Participants receiving control tDCS showed a 3.70%±2.0 SE improvement in task performance with training, while verum tDCS resulted in 13.00%±2.7SE improvement—yielding a 254% relative learning increase (BF10=11.74). Among the 57 HCs, control stimulation improved performance 5.19%±2.86SE, while verum increased performance 13.66%±3.29SE—a 164% relative improvement. For the 28 MCI/AD participants, control tDCS improved performance 1.02%±2.47SE and verum 11.50±4.94SE, corresponding to a 1027% relative improvement. Greater modeled electric field magnitude (EFM) under the anode correlated with improved learning (β=0.49, t(26)=2.9, p=0.007). Verum tDCS induced greater BOLD responses in frontoparietal and salience networks, which also predicted improved learning outcomes (BF10=18). Strong evidence (BF10>10) was found for improved learning and memory using this tDCS protocol. MCI/AD participants receiving verum tDCS showed 122% greater learning than HC receiving control (n.s.), suggesting that this tDCS protocol reverses memory deficits caused by MCI/AD. EFM and BOLD fMRI results suggest that tDCS effects on specific frontoparietal brain networks may underlie this learning benefit. This technique may someday help to reduce the burden of dementia. [Formula presented] Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 9. Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) Keywords Alzheimer's, neuroimaging, aging, memory
