N2  - Symposium title Transcranial Pulse Stimulation: recent advances, challenges and pitfalls Abstract Transcranial pulse stimulation (TPS) is a non-invasive brain stimulation technique that utilizes shockwaves to modulate brain function. Preliminary evidence suggests that TPS has a potential therapeutic effect on depressive symptoms in patients with Alzheimer’s disease and major depressive disorder (MDD). In this talk, I will present first results from a randomized, double-blind, sham-controlled TPS trial in MDD. 61 patients were recruited so far in this ongoing trial targeting the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (MNI coordinates x=-38, y=+44, z=+26 mm, defined on individual T1-weighted MRIs). TPS treatment involved 3 TPS sessions per week for 4 weeks, with 1000 pulses per session. The interim analysis indicated significantly higher response and remission rates defined by the Montgomery-Asberg Depression Rating Scale in the active group compared to the sham group. I will then go on to present results from an almost finalized TPS trial targeting the primary motor cortex. This study aimed to examine TPS effects on behavioral performance using the Nine-hole peg test (NHPT), a standard test for measuring manual dexterity. The study was designed as a randomized, double-blind, sham-controlled, crossover trial with n=34 healthy subjects, applying a single session of 1000 TPS pulses to the primary motor cortex. Interim results revealed a significant increase in NHPT performance speed of the hand contralateral to the stimulation site after TPS, but not after sham stimulation. This effect was sustained for 40 minutes (measured in 10-minute intervals). Successful blinding was achieved in both trials and reported side effects were mild. In the last part of my talk, I will outline a recently commenced RCT that aims to examine the behavioral effects of stimulating deeper cortical regions such as bilateral anterior insular cortex and bilateral dorsal anterior cingulate cortex. Flanked by fMRI measurements, this research aims to unveil the utility of alternative treatment targets for depression. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 13. Other Brain Stimulation Technology
