N2  - Symposium title Unveiling the Mechanisms of tDCS in Neurorehabilitation: From Protection to Recovery Abstract Background: Cognitive impairment is a major challenge in neurorehabilitation across various neurological conditions, including multiple sclerosis (MS). Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS), when combined with cognitive training, offers a novel approach to enhancing cognitive function, particularly in a home-based, noninvasive context. Objectives: This study tested cognitive outcomes following a home-based, active vs. sham tDCS intervention combined with adaptive cognitive training in individuals with MS-related fatigue. Methods: Participants with MS and clinically significant fatigue were stratified by neurologic disability using the Expanded Disability Status Scale (EDSS) and randomized to receive either active or sham tDCS over 30 daily sessions, each lasting 20 minutes. The tDCS was applied to the left DLPFC (anode F3, cathode F4), paired with online cognitive training (BrainHQ). Cognitive function was evaluated as a secondary outcome using the Brief International Cognitive Assessment in MS (BICAMS) administered before and after the intervention. Results: Of the 117 participants, 92% completed all sessions. While both active and sham groups showed reductions in fatigue, significant improvements in cognitive function were observed in the active tDCS group (p = 0.035). These cognitive gains were most pronounced in participants with higher neurologic disability. Conclusion: Home-based tDCS combined with cognitive training demonstrated significant improvements in cognitive function, supporting its role as a valuable tool for neurorehabilitation. The findings emphasize the potential of remotely supervised tDCS for cognitive recovery in neurological conditions, particularly in individuals with more severe impairments, aligning with broader efforts to expand accessible and scalable neurorehabilitation strategies. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 9. Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) Keywords tDCS, home-based, Clinical trials, Neurorehabilitation
