N2  - Abstract Background: Mild cognitive impairment (MCI) is a prodromal stage of Alzheimer’s disease (AD), characterized by early neurodegenerative changes, particularly in white matter microstructure. Optimized transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) has been shown to modulate brain plasticity and may preserve white matter integrity. The relationship between optimized electrical field strength and white matter microstructure integrity in MCI patients, considering individual risk factors such as APOE ε4 carrier status, amyloid-beta (Aβ) deposition, and BDNF polymorphism, remains underexplored. This study aimed to evaluate the impact of effect modifiers on the association between electrical field strength and white matter integrity. Methods: Sixty-three MCI patients underwent 10 sessions of tDCS (2 mA, 20 minutes, left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex). Diffusion tensor imaging (DTI) was utilized to assess white matter microstructure integrity, quantified by fractional anisotropy (FA), mean diffusivity (MD), and radial diffusivity (RD). Partial correlation and regression analyses investigated the interactions between optimized electrical field strength and effect modifiers (Aβ deposition, APOE ε4, BDNF polymorphism) on white matter integrity, adjusting for covariates (age, sex, education). Results: Optimized electrical field (EF) strength significantly influenced white matter microstructure, with effects modulated by individual risk factors for Alzheimer's disease. Aβ deposition moderated EF's impact on mean and radial diffusivity in the right superior longitudinal fasciculus (P < 0.015). APOE ε4 carriers showed greater reductions in radial diffusivity (P = 0.021). BDNF polymorphism also modified EF's effects, with increased fractional anisotropy in the right uncinate fasciculus seen in Met allele carriers (P < 0.02). Conclusion: This study highlights the importance of considering individual risk factors for AD when evaluating the effects of optimized electrical field strength on white matter microstructure integrity in MCI patients. The findings suggest that tDCS-induced neuroplasticity is modulated by genetic and pathological factors, reinforcing the potential of precision medicine approaches in non-invasive brain stimulation therapies for AD prevention. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 9. Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) Keywords tDCS, individualized factor, alzheimer's disease, white matter microstructure integrity
