N2  - Abstract Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) has gained significant interest for its potential to modulate cognitive functions and as a treatment option in various cognitive disorders. However, we still do not know 'where', 'when', and 'how' tDCS modulates information encoding by neurons, to lead to the changes in cognitive functions. The clinical application of tDCS has been hampered by significant variability in its cognitive outcomes. Without elucidating these fundamental unknowns, the causes of its outcome variability and long-term safety remain elusive, challenging the standardization and effective application of tDCS in clinical settings. Our study investigates the effects of tDCS, applied over the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (dlPFC), on cognitive abilities and individual cell activity in the context of cognitive tasks. There were practice-related behavioural adaptation and changes in simultaneously recorded activity of prefrontal neurons. Application of the tDCS attenuated both these behavioural and neuronal adaptations when compared to sham. At a single-cell level, we also found that following tDCS, neuronal firing rate was more likely to exhibit task-specific modulation than after sham stimulation. Here, we show that modulation of cognitive functions by the tDCS of the prefrontal cortex is accompanied by alterations in prefrontal cortical cell activity ('where') during distinct trial phases ('when'). Importantly, tDCS led to task-specific and state-dependent alterations in prefrontal cell activities ('how'). Our findings suggest a shift from the view that the tDCS effects are merely due to polarity-specific shifts in cortical excitability and instead, propose a more complex mechanism of action for tDCS that encompasses various aspects of cortical neuronal activity. Research Category and Technology and Methods Translational Research: 5. Other Transcranial Electrical Stimulation (tES) Keywords Transcranial Brain Stimulation, Prefrontal cortex, Single neuron activity, Direct current stimulation
