N2  - Abstract Background Mild cognitive impairment (MCI) patients experience cognitive decline, necessitating the exploration of non-pharmacological interventions such as transcranial current stimulation (tCS), a non-invasive neuromodulation technique that has shown promise in improving cognitive function with minimal side effects. This study aims to compare the effects of theta tACS and gamma tACS on cognitive function in MCI patients, addressing the gap in research to identify the most effective therapeutic intervention for the disease. Method In a randomized, active-control, pre-post, double-blinded, single intervention study, 47 subjects(16 male) aged over 60 participated. All participants were clinically diagnosed of MCI based on DSM-5 criteria for mild neurocognitive disorder or MCI criteria defined by Peterson. All participants signed the informed consent. The Digit Span test was performed to measure attention, short-term memory and working memory. Participants repeat a sequence of numbers as presented (forward) and in reverse order (backward). Visual attention and task-switching abilities were measured by TMT-A(Trail-Making Test A). Results 1. Digit Span In the Digit Span Forward task, a significant main effect of pre/post was observed (p=0.001). Post-hoc analysis revealed a significant increase in performance in the gamma group, with scores improving from pre-intervention (4.94) to post-intervention (5.56) (p=0.048). 2. TMT-A In the TMT-A task, no significant pre-post differences were observed in completion time across all groups. Discussion Gamma tACS showed a positive impact on cognitive function improvement in MCI patients, consistent with previous research, while theta tACS did not demonstrate significant cognitive improvements in MCI patients, despite its effectiveness in the general population. This difference may be due to theta-gamma coupling's role in cognitive functions, with gamma tACS effectively influencing this coupling in MCI patients, who typically exhibit higher slow-wave and lower fast-wave proportions, while theta tACS does not. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 8. Transcranial Alternating Current Stimulation (tACS) Keywords mild cognitive impairment, tACS, digit span test, trail-making test
