N2  - Abstract Persistent post-traumatic headaches (PTH) following mild traumatic brain injury (mTBI) are crucial determinants of prolonged recovery time and poor rehabilitation outcomes. Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) has been shown to have efficacy for PTH, depression, and cognitive impairments. Yet, there have not been biomarker studies to predict responsiveness to rTMS in mTBI. Here, we report the preliminary data of a randomized sham-controlled trial using high-frequency rTMS for PTH and post-concussion symptoms (PCS) in mTBI, with an exploration of biomarkers predictive of recovery. Six participants were enrolled (27 to 50 y/o, all females, 6 mos to 10 yrs post-mTBI). Prior to the trial, all participants received standard care but the PTH and PCS persisted outside the typical prognostic time window. 10-Hz rTMS was administered at the left primary motor cortex (2000 pulses/session, 12 sessions). Outcome measures were completed at baseline and following the completion of rTMS, including the headache impact test (HIT-6), Post-Concussion Symptom Scale (PCSS), and neurophysiological measures of cortical excitation and inhibition, namely resting motor threshold (RMT), intracortical inhibition (ICF), inhibition, short- and long-interval intracortical inhibition (SICI, LICI), cortical silent period (cSP), and ipsilateral silent period (iSP). The HIT-6 decreased 11.6% in the active group and 3.4% in the sham group. PCSS reduction was similar in both groups (active: 31.2%; sham: 28.9%). ICF increased 36.4% in the active group but decreased 22.2% in the sham group. LICI and cSP increased (126.4% and 16.9%, respectively) with active treatment but remained unchanged with sham treatment. Greater baseline cSP was associated with lower PCSS following rTMS (ρ=-0.89, p=0.02). Greater baseline iSP was associated with more changes in PCSS (ρ=0.83, p=0.04). Greater baseline RMT was associated with more changes in HIT-6 (ρ=0.94, p=0.005). Neurophysiological measures of cortical inhibition and facilitation could be biomarkers to predict responsiveness to rTMS in mTBI. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords Concussion, Post-traumatic headaches, Neurophysiology, Prediction
