N2  - Abstract Nearly four years into the pandemic, managing Post-Acute Sequelae of SARS-CoV-2 (PASC) remains a significant challenge, incurring increased healthcare costs and uncertainties in treatment due to the complex pathophysiology of COVID-19. Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) is being explored as a non-pharmacological intervention for PASC. Recognized for its safety, tolerability, and compatibility with cognitive training, tDCS provides a promising approach to alleviate PASC symptoms. Previous studies identified functional brain alterations in PASC patients, particularly in the olfactory cortex, cingulate cortex, thalamus, and cerebellum and associations with cognitive impairments. In this double-blind randomized clinical trial, we evaluated whether an intensive tDCS protocol combined with cognitive training could enhance cognitive function and mood in PASC patients while assessing changes in resting-state functional connectivity. Sixty participants were recruited. Participants underwent neuropsychological assessments at baseline and after a four-week treatment of daily 20-minute sessions of active or sham tDCS combined with cognitive training. Both groups showed improvements in mood and overall cognition. In the neuroimaging subsample, functional connectivity between bilateral cerebellar regions and with the lateral occipital cortex and inferior temporal gyrus increased significantly more in the active tDCS group compared to the sham tDCS. Additionally, connectivity between bilateral cerebellar regions with bilateral occipital pole, and connectivity between the right frontal operculum cortex with bilateral supramarginal gyrus, right middle temporal gyrus, and inferior frontal gyrus (pars opercularis) correlated with Montreal Cognitive Assessment (MoCA) score improvements more positively for the active tDCS group. Both active and sham tDCS with cognitive training groups benefited from the treatment. The functional connectivity enhancements were predominantly observed in areas with previously reported connectivity alterations in PASC, which were also correlated previously with deficits across various cognitive domains. Research Category and Technology and Methods Translational Research: 9. Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) Keywords Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation, Post-Acute Cognitive Impairment Sequelae of COVID-19, Resting-state functional connectivity
