N2  - Symposium title Tele-tDCS: Protocols, Progress, and Prospects in Remote Brain Stimulation Abstract tDCS is a non-invasive brain stimulation technique showing promise in managing multiple sclerosis (MS) symptoms like fatigue, cognitive impairment, and motor dysfunction. Remotely supervised tDCS (RS-tDCS) enhances accessibility by allowing home-based interventions. We present findings from two Class I sham-controlled randomized controlled trials (RCTs) evaluating RS-tDCS for symptom management. The BOOST-MS-Fatigue Trial assessed tDCS effects on fatigue and cognitive impairment in 135 participants. They received either active or sham tDCS paired with cognitive training (BrainHQ) over 30 sessions (6 weeks, daily Monday-Friday). Outcomes were measured at baseline and post-intervention. The Hand Dexterity and tDCS trial evaluated tDCS's impact on hand function in 60 participants with progressive MS. Participants received either active or sham tDCS targeting the primary motor cortex, combined with 30-minute manual dexterity exercises over 20 sessions (4 weeks, daily Monday-Friday). Dexterity was assessed at baseline and follow-up. In the BOOST-MS-Fatigue Trial, over 92% of participants completed more than 25 sessions. Both groups showed significant improvements in fatigue and cognitive functioning, but without significant differences, providing the first Class I evidence for home-based tDCS. In the motor trial, 98% of participants completed the majority of sessions, with the active tDCS group showing significant improvement in hand dexterity compared to the sham group, demonstrating the feasibility and efficacy of home-based tDCS. RS-tDCS is a feasible and effective method for delivering neuromodulation therapy to individuals with MS, highlighting the potential of home-based tDCS to manage multiple MS symptoms and supporting its scalability for future clinical applications. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 9. Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) Keywords tDCS, Home-based, Clinical trials, Neurorehabilitation
