N2  - Abstract This study investigates the impact of stress on working memory (WM) performance and explores the potential mitigating effects of transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) over the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (dlPFC) and ventromedial prefrontal cortex (vmPFC). Utilizing a crossover, randomized, single-blind, sham-controlled design with 78 subjects, we assessed stress induction within subjects and stimulation conditions between subjects. Stress was induced using aversive video clips, and WM performance was measured using a verbal N-back task (2, 3, and 4-back loads). We analyzed physiological markers (cortisol, heart rate, and heart rate variability), behavioral responses, and electroencephalographic (EEG) changes during aversive clips and WM tasks. The aversive video clips effectively induced stress, evidenced by increased state anxiety, negative affect, elevated salivary cortisol levels, and decreased heart rate variability. EEG data revealed stress-related disruptions in top-down control and heightened bottom-up processing. These findings validate the use of aversive video clips to reliably induce psychological stress in experimental settings. Stress-impaired WM performance in the sham condition at a specific load (3-back) in a verbal N-back task. Anodal tDCS over the vmPFC area improved WM task performance and, along with dlPFC stimulation, significantly blunted cortisol release under stress conditions. EEG analysis indicated that vmPFC stimulation decreased the P2 ERP component and increased task-related alpha desynchronization, suggesting reduced distractions and enhanced focus. Our results highlight the vmPFC as a promising target for interventions aimed at mitigating stress-induced cognitive deficits. The study contributes to developing targeted strategies to enhance resilience against acute stress, demonstrating that focal brain stimulation over the vmPFC can effectively reduce stress-related WM impairments and cortisol response. Research Category and Technology and Methods Translational Research: 9. Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) Keywords tDCS, Stress, Working Memory, EEG
