N2  - Abstract Introduction: Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) is a non-invasive brain stimulation method that applies a low-intensity current to the brain to apply neuromodulation. It is a cheap and safe procedure that may serve as a supplementary intervention for conditions like dementia, anxiety, and depression. However, previous results have been variable due to inconsistency amongst clinical trials. Our work aims to develop a fully automatic pipeline to predict electrical current flow in response to intervention. This will improve the consistency of tDCS trials by providing a basis for predicting intervention response. Materials and Methods: This study uses data from a Phase III clinical trial on cognitive training and tDCS for cognitive improvements. The trial recruited participants between 65-89 years old and with age-related cognitive decline. The T1-weighted Magnetic Resonance images from these participants were segmented into 11 tissue labels: white matter, grey matter, eyes, cerebrospinal fluid, air, major artery, cancellous bone, cortical bone, skin, fat, and muscle. This process was performed by trained manual segmentors using a semi-automatic process. We employ a deep learning method-based transformers to predict electrical current flow. Our method employs special loss regularizations to improve the model’s generalizability and calibration across individual scans and electrode montages. Users may enter a desired electrode montage in addition to the unique MRI for a custom output. Results and Discussion: The pipeline can generate results on the scale of minutes, unlike physics-based systems that can take 1-3 hours. The current results obtain a structural similarity index measure of 0.8208 and an expected calibration error of 0.02821. Conclusion: The current work proves the feasibility of the pipeline by successfully using deep learning to capture individual brain anatomy and predict electrical current flow. Ultimately, this will lead to a system that can optimize tDCS stimulation parameters based on predicting intervention progress in-silico. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 9. Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) Keywords tDCS, Deep Learning, Artificial Intelligence, Digital Twins
