N2  - Mild cognitive impairment (MCI) and dementia due to neurodegenerative disorders (ND) cause deficits in various cognitive domains. Excitatory noninvasive brain stimulation (NIBS) approaches, such as anodal transcranial electrical current stimulation (tES) and repetitive high-frequency transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) modulate neural activity, aiming to enhance cognitive functions and slow down neurodegenerative processes. Recent studies highlight their potential in improving general cognition, memory, executive, and language functions, offering a non-pharmacological management of patients with MCI and dementia due to ND. The mechanisms underlying these benefits are believed to involve synaptic plasticity and network connectivity enhancement. However, the effectiveness of NIBS varies, necessitating further research to identify responsive patient subgroups, and optimize protocols, including development of feasible self-administered home-based applications. This chapter summarizes the evidence from randomized, sham-controlled studies, underscoring the therapeutic potential of NIBS in patients with MCI and dementia, advocating for Phase III-clinical trials to fully ascertain its efficacy, and mechanism of action in the neurodegenerative disease spectrum.
