N2  - Introduction: Psychotic depression involves severe symptoms like depression, psychomotor issues, guilt, suicidal thoughts, and cognitive impairment, requiring accurate diagnosis and treatment. Aims & Objectives: To evaluate the effect of adjunctive bilateral sequential theta burst stimulation (TBS) on depressive and psychotic symptoms, and central executive network (CEN) functional connectivity in patients with psychotic depression. To explore associations between demographic, clinical factors, and symptoms in the active TBS group. Method: A sham-controlled clinical trial with 30 participants (15 active, 15 sham) using purposive sampling. Baseline measures include fMRI, Hamilton scales, and Brief Psychiatric Rating Scale. Participants receive active or sham TBS on the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex for 2 weeks. Assessments are repeated at 2 and 4 weeks. Results: Clinical and fMRI assessments analyzed using SPSS 28.0. Conclusion: Bihemispheric prefrontal TBS shows promise for major depressive disorder, but its impact on psychotic depression needs investigation. Key words: psychotic depression, cognitive impairment, HDRS, BPRS, TBS.
