N2  - Alzheimer's disease (AD) is one of the most challenging neurodegenerative disorders, with limited therapeutic options currently available. Recent advancements in noninvasive neuromodulation techniques, including acoustic, light, and magnetic stimulation, have opened new avenues for AD intervention. These techniques aim to modulate neural activity, enhance neuroplasticity, and mitigate the pathological hallmarks of AD, such as amyloid-β (Aβ) plaques and tau tangles. Sound-based interventions, particularly pulse low-frequency and low-intensity transcranial ultrasound stimulation (TUS), have demonstrated remarkable potential in preclinical and clinical studies. This talk will highlight the neuromodulation studies utilizing TUS for AD intervention and treatment. Ultimately, I will introduce the treatment effects of TUS in AD mouse models. We developed a customized TUS instrument and evaluated a series of sonication parameters, specifically exploring their impact on cortical A β plaque aggregation. Thirty-three aging 6- to 8-month-old 5 ×FAD mouse models were randomly divided into three groups: a treated group receiving parameter A, a treated group receiving parameter B, and a sham control group. The treated groups underwent TUS experiments consisting of a 15-minute session every other day for seven sessions. In contrast, the sham group had similar experiments except for sending ultrasound signals into the brain. We found that TUS efectively facilitated Aβ burden clearance (27.58% and 4759% reduction compared to the sham group) in the 5×FAD models. These fndings underscore the efcacy of ultrasound-based interventions and highlight its potential as a promising non-invasive therapeutic strategy for AD. These preclinical findings may provide novel insights into AD intervention in the clinic via a noninvasive brain stimulation approach.
