N2  - Purpose of Study Hypoxic ischemic encephalopathy (HIE) stems from global cerebral ischemia (GCI) that occurs during the post perinatal period and is associated with lifelong neurosensory and cognitive impairments. In severe cases, where delivery room resuscitation involves chest compressions, the current standard of care is to use 100% fraction of inspired oxygen (FiO2). Additionally, transient receptor potential melastatin 2 (TRPM2) channels are known to be activated by oxidative stress and are implicated in cellular and function impairment in GCI. The primary aim of this study is to elucidate the effects of using 100% or 21% FiO2 during resuscitation on synaptic plasticity using a novel rat cardiac arrest model of HIE. We also investigate the role of TRPM2 channels in synaptic plasticity following HIE. We hypothesize that resuscitation using 100% FiO2 leads to worse neurological outcomes compared to resuscitation using 21% FiO2, and TRPM2 channel inhibition may be neuroprotective. Methods Used GCI was achieved in intubated post-natal day 10 rats using intravenous (IV) potassium chloride (KCl) resulting in asystole and confirmed with EKG. After 12 minutes of asystole, chest compressions were performed, intravenous epinephrine administered, and either 100% or 21% FiO2 was delivered. Control animals underwent procedural instrumentation but did not receive KCl and were randomized to receive either 100% or 21% FiO2. A single dose of a TRPM2 antagonist, tatM2NX, or saline was administered IV immediately prior to extubation. Hippocampal CA1 synaptic plasticity was assessed by measuring long-term potentiation (LTP) along the Schaffer-Collateral-CA1 pathway 14 days post-GCI. We quantified the increase in field excitatory post-synaptic potential slope 60 minutes post-theta-burst stimulation (TBS) and compared it to the 10 minutes before TBS (set at 100%). Results are presented as mean±SD. Statistical analysis by ANOVA. Summary of Results In the 100% FiO2 group, LTP was impaired post-GCI compared to control (111±19%, n=8, vs 173±35%, n=7, p=0.001). In the 21% FiO2 group, LTP showed no change compared to control (153±26%, n=9, vs 166±24% n=11, p=0.802). Comparing both post-CGI groups, LTP was not impaired in the 21% FiO2 GCI group compared to the 100% FiO2 group (p=0.018). Animals resuscitated with 100% FiO2 who received tatM2NX had preserved LTP compared to animals treated with saline (168±26%, n=2, vs 117±16%, n=3, p=0.292). Conclusions Our novel cardiac arrest model of HIE demonstrated differences between resuscitation with 21% or 100% FiO2. Animals resuscitated with 100% FiO2 had impaired synaptic plasticity, which is associated with worsened long-term neurological outcomes with learning and memory. Our data further suggests that inhibition of TRPM2 channels may preserve hippocampal synaptic plasticity in GCI. These results provide the framework for further investigating the use of 100% or 21% FiO2 during resuscitation and improving long-term neurological outcomes in patients with HIE.
