N2  - Introduction: Inflammatory pathologies are sources of painful suffering and alterations in the quality of life, sometimes leading to serious consequences: multiorgan failure, cognitive disorders, death, etc. Vagus nerve stimulation (VNS) produces a cholinergic anti-inflammatory effect described in various experimental models and deserves to be evaluated in humans. Methods: We present here the preliminary observations of the effect of non-invasive VNS as adjuvant treatment in 33 patients suffering from drug-resistant ankylosing spondylitis (AS) treated in our hospital with vagus nerve stimulation for pain. Patients received one hour of VNS per week for 8weeks. Stimulation is carried out using a transcutaneous neurostimulator (TENS eco 2 Schwa Médico) with an electrode allowing non-invasive stimulation of the intra-auricular branch of the vagus nerve at the level of the concha of the ear. Questionnaires assessing the progression of the disease (BASDAI, BASFI), as well as anxiety, depression (HAD) and pain (VAS) are collected and analyzed during the treatment period. Results: Significant improvements in disease activity scores (BASDAI, BASFI), mood (HAD) and pain (VAS) were observed at the end of the treatment period in AS patients in comparison at the beginning. Conclusions: SNV seems very promising in inflammatory pathologies and particularly in cases of drug resistance. We are currently conducting randomized studies in order to validate these observations: NCT04286373 and NCT04774705.
