N2  - Background: Conflicting results regarding the effects of combined non-pharmacological interventions on cognitive function prompted this study to develop a combined intervention, MMNCE (music-based exercise, multi-domain cognitive training synchronized with neurostimulation, and emotion-regulation education). This study compared its effectiveness with MCS (cognitive training synchronized with sham neurostimulation) in promoting cognitive protection in older adults with normal cognition. Methods: The single-blind, three-arm randomized controlled trial was conducted in community daytime care centers in Xuzhou, China. 166 older adults (mean age: 68.95 ± 6.27 years) were randomly assigned to MMNCE, MCS, or NIC (no-intervention control) groups. Primary outcomes included Montreal Cognitive Assessment (MoCA) scores and executive function task scores, assessed at baseline, 12 weeks (primary endpoint), 24 weeks, and 36 weeks. Findings: At 12 weeks, 124 participants completed the intervention. MMNCE showed larger effect size than MCS, with significant improvements in MoCA total scores and domains, including visuospatial ability, naming, attention, abstract reasoning, and episodic memory, compared to NIC (η²p = 0.15 to 0.54). Furthermore, MMNCE outperformed MCS in MoCA abstraction (η²p = 0.11; 95%CI: 0.03 to 1) and demonstrated superior cognitive-preserving effects among participants with central obesity, ≥2 children, no regular exercise, regular social interactions, and <6 hours of sleep. In addition, MMNCE improved physical function and reduced depressive symptoms. Interpretation: This study highlights MMNCE as an effective nonpharmacological intervention for preserving cognitive function in older adults. Further research is warranted to explore its impact on individuals across various stages of cognitive decline. Trial Registration: Registered at https://www.chictr.org.cn/showproj.html?proj=17915; trial number: ChiCTR2200064582. Funding: This work was supported by the General Project of the National Social Science Foundation of China (21BGL229) and the General Research Project of Universities’ Philosophy and Social Science in Jiangsu Province (2020SJA1145). Declaration of Interest: The authors report no conflicts of interest. Ethical Approval: This study was conducted under the Code of Ethics of the World Medical Association (Declaration of Helsinki). The Biomedical Ethics Review Committee of Peking University granted ethical approval for this study (IRB00001052-22093), and all participants signed informed consent.
