N2  - It has been demonstrated that intermittent theta burst stimulation(iTBS) is an effective method for alleviating neurological deficits resulting from stroke. However, there has been a paucity of animal experiments aimed at elucidating the neurobiological mechanisms underlying its beneficial effects. Accordingly, the present experiments focused on the effects of iTBS on behavioral and neuropathology in ischemia/reperfusion (I/R)-injured rats and explored the underlying mechanisms. A rat I/R injury model was established by middle cerebral artery occlusion (MCAO). SD rats were randomly divided into the sham operation group, the MCAO group and the iTBS + MCAO group (once a day for 10 days). There were 18 rats in each group, and cognitive function, myelin regeneration, microglia, inflammation, and MAPK signaling pathway expression were evaluated in each group. The results demonstrated that iTBS enhanced the performance of animals in Y-maze and Open Field Test and facilitated the recuperation of cognitive functions following I/R injury. Furthermore, iTBS mitigated myelin damage, facilitated myelin regeneration, reduced the number of M1 microglia, elevated the number of M2 microglia, and suppressed the inflammatory response. Further studies revealed that iTBS improved cognitive function in I/R-injured rats, at least in part, by inhibiting the ERK1/2 and JNK signaling pathways to promote the transformation of M2 microglia, suppressing inflammation, and providing a favorable microenvironment for myelin regeneration.
