N2  - Background/Objective(s): Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a progressive disease of the central nervous system characterized by widespread damage to the brain and spinal cord.MS causes motor, cognitive, and neuropsychiatric symptoms, all of which can occur independently of each other.The most common cognitive symptoms include deficits in complex attention, information processing efficiency, executive function, processing speed, and long-term memory.These deficits negatively impact many aspects of daily life, such as the ability to manage one's household, participate fully in society, and maintain employment, all of which can affect a patient's overall quality of life. The increased use of neuroimaging techniques in MS patients has improved our understanding of the structural and functional changes in the brain that characterize the disease, although much remains to be learned. Additionally, testing treatment efforts for cognitive impairment in MS is still in its early stages. Material(s) and Method(s): This study is a randomized clinical trial. We enrolled 120 MS patients and divided them into four groups (30 in each group): tDCS alone, tDCS combined with application-assisted cognitive rehabilitation, application-assisted cognitive rehabilitation alone, and a tDCS sham protocol. Prior to and after the intervention, we conducted diffusion tensor imaging (DTI) to assess brain connectivity and measured brain-derived neurotrophic factor (BDNF) levels as a marker of neuroplasticity. Acetylcholinesterase inhibition was also evaluated as a biomarker for learning. Cognitive function was assessed using several tests: the Symbol Digit Modalities Test (SDMT) for processing speed, the IVA Continuous Performance Test (IVA-CPT) for attention, and the Iowa Gambling Task (IGT) for frontal lobe function Result(s): Our findings revealed that patients receiving both tDCS and cognitive rehabilitation exhibited significantly higher levels of BDNF and greater fractional anisotropy as measured by DTI compared to the other groups. Furthermore, cognitive assessments indicated notable improvements in cognitive function for this group. Patients who received tDCS alone also demonstrated significant cognitive enhancements, with application-assisted cognitive rehabilitation alone showing moderate improvements Conclusion(s): The results suggest that combining tDCS with application-assisted cognitive rehabilitation may serve as an effective strategy for addressing cognitive impairments in patients with multiple sclerosis. This combination not only enhances neuroplasticity, as evidenced by increased BDNF levels and improved DTI metrics, but also leads to measurable improvements in cognitive performance. Our study highlights the potential of integrating neuromodulation techniques with cognitive rehabilitation to optimize therapeutic outcomes for individuals with MS. Future research should explore the long-term effects of this combined approach and its applicability in broader clinical settings.
